<HEADLINE> More U.S. Computer Makers Sell Products Online </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, February 20 (Xinhua) -- While American customers
are becoming more comfortable buying clothing and books online,
analysts said that they have not yet begun making major purchases.
</P>
<P>
Websites offering advice about cars, computers and travel have
expanded over the past two years in the United States. Customers
do their research on the Net and go to stores to pick up things
they want to buy. But this is beginning to change. More and more
businesses have started to realized that the Internet can be
a cheaper method of selling products.
</P>
<P>
Major computer makers, such as Apple Computer Inc., Compaq
Computer Corp. and Hewlett-Packard Co., are selling their products
over the Web. Dell Computer Corp. boasts of more than four million
U.S. dollars worth of products and services sold over the Internet
each day.
</P>
<P>
For a time, IBM seems not to envious, lavishing money on television
ads touting its E-commerce software suite. Now it also plans to
start selling PCs over the Web. One IBM senior executive said
recently that the manufacturer intended to offer a way for
customers to configure and order computers via its Website in
the "near future." In fact, the decision is part of a larger
initiative to improve the performance of the PC company, which now
ranks second in worldwide market share behind Compaq and ahead of
Dell and NEC.
</P>
<P>
IBM has resisted taking this step for fear it might alienate
the company's resellers. However, under the proposed plan,
resellers will ship the products to customers in a move designed
to undercut any possible opposition from its distribution channel.
</P>
<P>
Analysts say that the kinds of customers who buy computers over
the Web tend to be experienced users shopping for price and
performance. It's still unclear whether the popularity of
Web-based PC sales will transfer into major incremental gains in
the business for computer makers.
</P>
<P>
With ever-increasing online sales, banks, credit card companies
and businesses will have to figure out better ways to communicate
with each other. Analysts say it may take some time for those
issues to be settled. The adoption of the Security Electronic
Transaction (SET) specification used to verify all the parties
engaged in a credit card purchase, for instance, is at least a
year away. 
</P>
</TEXT>
