<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yemeni President Visits UAE </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, February 21 (Xinhua) -- Yemeni President Ali
Abdullah Saleh arrived here Saturday on a three-day visit, mainly
for discussions on the lastest developments in the Gulf region,
especially the Iraq-U.N. crisis over arms inspections.
</P>
<P>
The United Arab Emirates' official Wam news agency said Saleh
is expected to hold talks with President Sheikh Zayed bin Sultan
Al-Nahyan and other senior officials on "the latest developments
in the Gulf" and "ways of strengthening bilateral relations."
</P>
<P>
Wam gave no further details, but informed sources here said his
visit will focus on the current Iraq-U.N. crisis triggered by
Iraq's refusal to grant full access to U.N. weapons inspectors to
sites suspected of containing chemical and biological weapons.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. and Britain have threaten a military strike if
diplomatic efforts fail to persuade Baghdad to open up suspected
sites to U.N. inspectors.
</P>
<P>
Yemen was cautious to make its stand clear towards the
U.S. war talks, but the UAE has openly opposed the use of force
against Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Yemen was treated coldly by the UAE and other Gulf Arab states
- all anti-Iraq allies of the U.S. in the 1990-91 crisis - in the
past seven years due to its sympathy for the Iraqi authority. It
began to seek ways of improving ties with the Gulf neighbors after
the Gulf war.
</P>
<P>
Sanaa has applied to join the Gulf Cooperation Council (GCC), a
political, economic and defense alliance formed by the Gulf Arab
countries in 1981, but the GCC has so far given no reply. 
</P>
</TEXT>
