<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 1500 GMT, February 21 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI -- Vietnamese Prime Minister Phan Van Khai has given
green light to a plan to consider the establishment of special
economic zones in the country, Vietnam News Agency reported
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Phan made the decision after a meeting with Deputy Prime
Ministers Nguyen Tan Dung, Nguyen Cong Tan, Ngo Xuan Loc and Pham
Gia Khiem, and the director of the management board of industrial
zones, Le Xuan Trinh. (Vietnam-Special Economic Zones)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
LONDON -- The Irish Republican Army's political wing Sinn Fein
said on Saturday that the ceasefire remained intact despite a
massive bombing in Northern Ireland Friday night.
</P>
<P>
A car bomb exploded outside a police station in the
predominantly Protestant town of Moira, southwest of Belfast,
injuring 11 people. The incident took place just hours after Sinn
Fein's expulsion from the multi-party peace talks.
</P>
<P>
Sinn Fein leader Gerry Adams said he "regretted" the bombing at
Moira, and called for an end to all armed actions. (Irish-Sinn
Fein)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
MOSCOW -- Estonia has decided to send disaster-relief
volunteers and medical workers to participate in the military
action against Iraq within 48 hours of the failure of
U.N. mediation, Iterfax news agency reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The decision was adopted at a national security meeting
summoned by Estonian President Lennart Meri Friday night.
</P>
<P>
The agency said the meeting examined the current situation in
the Gulf region and reviewed obligations contained in a joint
statement issued by the heads of state of the three Baltic
countries on January 16. (Estonia-Iraq Crisis)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
TOKYO -- Japan launched a communications and broadcasting test
satellite on Saturday but failed to put it into geostationary
orbit after the second stage of the H-2 rocket carrying it failed,
a report reaching here said.
</P>
<P>
The two-stage 5H-2 rocket blasted off from Tanegashima Space
Center in Kagoshima Prefecture, about 1,000 kilometers southwest
of Tokyo, at 4:55 p.m. (local time), and released the satellite
into space about 30 minutes after the lift-off, the report said.
</P>
<P>
But the satellite, called COMETS, could not enter geostationary
orbit 36,000 KM above Earth as scheduled due to the second-stage
rocket failure, the report said. (Japan-Satellite)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM -- The deadly disease of Rift Valley Fever (RVF)
has spread into Tanzania, media reports said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Two cases of the fever have been discovered in Loliondo in the
northern region of Arusha, close to the Tanzania-Kenya border,
said Chris Daborn, country project manager of Vetaid-Tanzanian, a
British non-governmental organization which assists indigenous
people to be aware of ways to combat animal diseases.
(Tanzania-Disease)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
LAGOS -- Member countries of the Economic Community of West
African States (ECOWAS) have agreed to raise the strength of the
sub-regional peace-keeping force ECOMOG's troops in Sierra Leone
to 15,000, Nigerian Foreign Minister Tom Ikimi has said.
</P>
<P>
Ikimi made the announcement Thursday in Freetown, where a
delegation of ECOWAS foreign ministers were assessing the
situation, preparatory to president Ahmed Tejan Kabbah's return to
power. (Nigeria-ECOMOG troops)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BAGHDAD -- U.N. Secretary General Kofi Annan Saturday started
talks with Iraqi Deputy Prime Minister Tariq Aziz on the
inspections of presidential sites.
</P>
<P>
The talks were held in Iraqi Foreign Ministry, the Iraqi News
Agency said. But no details were disclosed.
</P>
<P>
Annan arrived in Baghdad Friday evening in what is believed to
be the last-ditch effort to seek a peaceful solution to the
standoff of arms inspection between Iraq and the United Nations
Special Commission. (Iraq-Annan-Talks) (
</P>
