<HEADLINE> Saudi Arabia Wishes Annan's Mission Success </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, February 21 (Xinhua) -- Saudi Foreign Minister
Prince Saud Al-Faisal said Saturday in Riyadh he had high hopes
for the success of U.N. Secretary General Kofi Annan's Baghdad
visit.
</P>
<P>
He made the remark while greeting former Iranian President
Hashemi Rafsanjani who arrived in Riyadh on an official visit,
according to a report by the Kuwait News Agency.
</P>
<P>
He said "this is what every peace-loving person wishes and we
pray for God for the success of Annan's mission," but he added
"the decision in the end is in the hands of the Iraqi government."
</P>
<P>
Annan flew to Baghdad Friday in a last-ditch effort to find a
diplomatic solution to the current Iraq crisis over weapons
inspections and avert a military confrontation. The United States
and Britain have threaten sustained aerial strike to force Iraqi
compliance.
</P>
<P>
Saudi Arabia is opposed to a military strike against Iraq but
urged Baghdad to comply fully with the UN resolutions.
</P>
<P>
Saudi King Fahd Ibn Abdul Aziz has called for exhausting all
diplomatic efforts to bring the crisis to an end. 
</P>
</TEXT>
