<HEADLINE> Annan Remains Optimistic About Mediation Efforts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, February 21 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General
Kofi Annan remained optimistic about his efforts to head off U.S.
military strikes against Iraq as he resumed his talks with Iraqi
officials, U.N. officials said here Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Annan, who is now in the Iraqi capital of Baghdad on a critical
mission to peacefully resolve the Iraqi crisis, held talks for
more than three hours earlier in the day with Iraqi Deputy Prime
Minister Tareq Aziz and other Iraqi officials, the officials said.
</P>
<P>
"I am still optimistic," the U.N. chief said after briefing
diplomats on his talks.
</P>
<P>
But no details of the talks were disclosed.
</P>
<P>
Annan was holding an evening round of talks with Aziz, the
officials said.
</P>
<P>
The two men each took one senior official with them into the
talks aimed to resolve a row over weapons inspections on
presidential sites.
</P>
<P>
They were expected to be joined by other officials for plenary
session.
</P>
<P>
But the optimism in Baghdad was overshadowed by new U.S.
warnings and threats.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. States Department advised American citizens to leave
Iraq as soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
"Due to these ongoing tensions, all U.S. citizens are strongly
urged to avoid all travel to Iraq, and those already in Iraq are
advised to depart as soon as possible," the department said in a
travel warning issued Saturday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
