<HEADLINE> Tanzanian Airline Hires Plane to Expand Services </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, February 21 (Xinhua) -- The Air Tanzania Corporation
(ATC) has hired one Boeing 737-730 from a Mexican airline, TASEA, in
an effort to improve its flight services.
</P>
<P>
The ATC Public Relations Officer, Innocent Mungy told reporters
Saturday in Dar es Salaam that the aircraft has a carrying capacity of
130 passengers and is expected to arrive in Tanzania next week.
</P>
<P>
The flight will be used for both local and international flights,
Mungy said.
</P>
<P>
He said that since the corporation has expanded its international
flights to the Democratic Republic of Congo and Mozambique, there
is need to hire planes in order to survive in the cut-throat
competition.
</P>
<P>
" We are expecting to start our flights to the Democratic Republic
of Congo, particularly to Goma and Luxbumbashi towns, and the famous
tourism town of Pemba in Mozambique, a situation which forces us to
have a good aircraft," he said.
</P>
<P>
Mungy said that flights to Pemba are expected to start next month
and those to Goma and Luxbumbashi are scheduled to take off early April.
</P>
<P>
At present, ATC has two Boeing 737-200 with a carrying
capacity of 106 passengers each for both local and international
flights. 
</P>
</TEXT>
