<HEADLINE> 23 Ethiopian Towns to Get Semi-automatic </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, February 21 (Xinhua) -- The Ethiopian
Telecommunications Corporation said that it has been engaged in a
project aimed at rendering semi-automatic telephone services to
23 towns in north and south Gondar area, in the northwestern part
of the country.
</P>
<P>
According to a report reaching here from Gondar on Saturday,
Feseha Ketsela, manager of the northwestern branch of the
corporation, said the project will cost 867,000 U.S. Dollars.
</P>
<P>
Antennae, power generators and other imported equipment have
been delivered to the project sites, the report said.
</P>
<P>
There are only 160,000 telephone lines in Ethiopia.
</P>
<P>
Under a development program designed by the corporation,
Ethiopia will have no less than 850,000 telephone lines in the
coming one or two years, with 300 rural towns benefiting from the
program. 
</P>
</TEXT>
