<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-21 17:48 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egypt Wants Joint Projects to Harness Nile Water </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, February 21 (Xinhua) -- An Egyptian delegation left here
Saturday for the Rwandan capital Kigali to attend a five-day
conference on the Nile river, scheduled for Monday.
</P>
<P>
First Undersecretary of the Ministry of Public Works and Water
Resources Ahmed Fahmi, who led the team, told reporters before
departure that the conference will deal with ways of overcoming
problems facing the Nile Basin countries.
</P>
<P>
Egypt will submit a working paper expounding its water policy,
means of upgrading regional cooperation on the use of the Nile
water and the possibility of launching projects to make optimal
use of the river, he said.
</P>
<P>
The Nile basin countries - Egypt, Sudan, Tanzania, Uganda,
Rwanda, Eritrea, Burundi, Kenya, Zaire and Ethiopia - hold a
conference every year to address the Nile water problems.
</P>
<P>
There are differences among those countries over development
projects on the river, with some claiming that the water projects
have infringed on their rights.
</P>
<P>
Egypt has been accused of consuming more than its due by
setting up ambitious projects to irrigate deserts into arable
land. But it rejected the charge and urged the Nile countries to
launch joint ventures for their common good, instead of coming up
with a new Nile agreement.
</P>
<P>
The Nile countries are bounded by an agreement signed in 1959
as regards how much water they are entitled to, but some are
asking to amend it.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, Egypt has access to 55.5 billion cubic
meters of Nile water, which accounts for 99 percent of its sweet
water resources.
</P>
<P>
Ethiopia, eager to revise the 1959 agreement, has suspended the
joint meetings between its water experts and those of Egypt.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
