<DOCNO> XIE19980222.0013 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-21 18:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Annan, Aziz Start Second Round of Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, February 21 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary General Kofi
Annan entered into a second round of talks Saturday evening with
Iraqi Deputy Prime Minister Tariq Aziz to find a diplomatic way of
the Iraq-U.N. standoff over arms inspections.
</P>
<P>
After they finished the first round of talks earlier Saturday,
U.N. spokesman said that their talks were constructive, but
refused to elaborate.
</P>
<P>
Annan, who arrived here Friday evening, is expected to hold
talks Sunday directly with Iraqi President Saddam Hussein if his
talks with Aziz go on well.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. chief said upon arrival in Baghdad that he is
"reasonably optimistic" that he can find a solution to the crisis
in order to avert a military confrontation in the region.
</P>
<P>
But the United States has been reiterating that it may reject
any deal reached between Annan and Iraq that does not meet
U.S. demand and relevant U.N. resolutions on eliminating Iraq's
weapons of mass destruction.
</P>
<P>
In sharp contrast to an allegation made by U.S. President Bill
Clinton that one of Saddam's palaces was "about the size of
Washington D.C.," some 162 square kilometers, a U.N. technical
team which surveyed eight Iraqi presidential sites said Friday all
the eight sites altogether comprise an area of 31.5 square
kilometers.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. has been accusing Iraq of concealing weapons of mass
destruction in those presidential sites and demanding free access
by U.N. arms inspectors to those areas declared "off-limits" by
Baghdad.
</P>
<P>
In a sign of Arab support for Iraqi people, a delegation of the
United Arab Emirates Red Cross Society Saturday arrived in Baghdad
on board a plane carrying 40 tonnes of medicines and foodstuffs.
</P>
<P>
With talks between Annan and Aziz going on, eleven U.N. arms
inspection teams carried out their work smoothly Saturday and
inspected nine sites, said an Iraqi official. The Iraqi side was
very cooperative, he said.
</P>
<P>
He said a technical team of the International Atomic Energy
Agency, which arrived in Baghdad last week, proceeded with its
meetings Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Annan's visit here is seen as a "last-ditch" effort to bring
about a political and diplomatic solution to the Iraqi crisis. The
U.S. said a military strike can come at any time if diplomacy
fails to secure Saddam's compliance. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
