<DOCNO> XIE19980222.0014 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zanzibar Residents Spend a Day without Power, </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, February 21 (Xinhua) -- Tens of thousands of
Zanzibar residents Saturday endured sweatering heat and a
breakdown of water supply following a day-long power
interruption, said a report reaching here from Zanzibar.
</P>
<P>
State Fuel and Power Generation (SFPC) attributed power
interruption to major technical repairs made at Ras Kilomoni on
the mainland.
</P>
<P>
The Zanzibar isles in the Indian Ocean are connected to the
national power grid, receiving electricity via a submarine cable
from the mainland of Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
Business came to a standstill while most residents went out of
doors in anticipation of some cool sea breeze.
</P>
<P>
Women and children in almost all residential areas in the
Zanzibar municipality were seen rushing here and there in search
of water as taps went dry immediately after 9 a.m. when power was
disconnected.
</P>
<P>
Shopping proved a nightmare as customers grope into darkness.
Major hospitals in the Zanzibar municipality have suspended
operations due to lack of electricity.
</P>
<P>
Zanzibar urban residents get water supply from natural springs
at Chunga, Mwanyanya, Bweleo and Kijitoupele by use of
electricity-powered pumping machines. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
