<HEADLINE> U.S. Presses Japan to Play Bigger Role in Asia Recover </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, February 21 (Xinhua) -- America pressed Japan to play a
bigger role in helping Asia recover in a G-7 meeting of finance
ministers and central bankers which opens here Saturday.
</P>
<P>
In an hour-long bilateral meeting on the sidelines of the G-7
gathering, U.S. Treasury Secretary Rober Rubin delivered a stern
warning to his Japanese counterpart, Hikaru Matsunaga, reminding
him that Japan's measures to stimulate growth at home were simply
not good enough.
</P>
<P>
Rubin expressed his concern that "the Japanese economy is weak
and the Japanese external surplus is increasing," a Treasury
official told reporters after the meeting.
</P>
<P>
In response to this, Hikaru Matsunaga told Rubin that Japan's
first priority now was to pass the 1998/99 budget, a Japanese
Ministry of Finance source was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
However, it was believed that the ministers agreed that the
Asian crisis "makes strong domestic demand-led growth especially
important in all G-7 countries."
</P>
<P>
The issue of what Tokyo can do to help its neighbors by
stimulating demand at home has taken center state at Saturday's
meeting. The U.S. and its European partners maintain that
strengthening Japan's economy is the key to recovery in the entire
Asian region.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that Japan is considering calling for a common
currency system for Asia as part of its plan to support Asian
economies affected by the recent currency crisis. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
