<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> G-7 ECAs' Joint Statement in Support of Asia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, February 21 (Xinhua) -- The G-7 ECAs (export credit
agencies) and their relevant national authorities approved a
practical and immediate initiative to help stabilize the Asian
market.
</P>
<P>
This initiative will allow for continued trade flows that will
benefit the economies and support employment of all involved
countries, according to a joint statement released at a meeting of
G-7 finance ministers here Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Export credit agencies have a unique role in international
trade and are positioned to support and supplement the financing
of trade in the region.
</P>
<P>
Given the fundamental long-term strength of the Asian
economies, the reform programs being adopted by a number of
affected countries, and the commitments which the ECAs already
have in the region, the G-7 ECAs believe that there is a strong
case and need to maintain trade finance support to the region.
</P>
<P>
Last year, the ECAs supported some 15 billion U.S. dollars of
short-term credits to Indonesia, South Korea and Thailand alone.
</P>
<P>
The initiative builds on existing G-7 ECA programs and each
agency will continue to operate under its independent rules and
regulations.
</P>
<P>
In addition, these G-7 ECAs noted they remain open for medium-
and long-term creditworthy business.
</P>
<P>
In pursuing this multi-lateral initiative, the G-7 ECAs
recognize the importance of working with Asian nations in
overcoming current difficulties in order to maintain trade flows
and foster stable long-term growth. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
