<HEADLINE> U.S. Advises Americans to Quickly Leave Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, February 21 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. State Department
Saturday advised U.S. citizens to leave Iraq as soon as possible,
sending another sign that a military attack on Iraq may be
imminent.
</P>
<P>
"While diplomatic options have not been exhausted, the
government of Iraq continues to make provocative and
confrontational statements indicating its unwillingness to comply
with U.N. resolutions," the State Department said.
</P>
<P>
"Due to these ongoing tensions, all U.S. citizens are strongly
urged to avoid all travel to Iraq, and those already in Iraq are
advised to depart as soon as possible," it added.
</P>
<P>
The State Department could not say how many U.S. citizens are
in Iraq, but it was reported that the number would be small as
there is no U.S. embassy in Baghdad and severe restrictions
prevented U.S. businessmen from going to Iraq.
</P>
<P>
The Pentagon also warned, in a memorandum, Saturday that
journalists who stay in Iraq may be at risk.
</P>
<P>
"You should be aware that there is substantial risk involved in
sending people to Iraq during a period that could be highly
dangerous," the memorandum said.
</P>
<P>
"We will do our best to minimize civilian casualties; however,
the safety of any particular group of people, including
journalists, could be jeopardized in the event of military
action," it added.
</P>
<P>
On Friday, the State Department advised dependents and
non-emergency staff from U.S. diplomatic missions in Kuwait and
Israel to leave the two countries.
</P>
<P>
The warnings were made at a time when United Nations Secretary
General Kofi Annan was in Baghdad to avert the military conflict.
</P>
<P>
Annan said he remained optimistic as he sought a diplomatic
solution to the confrontation over Iraqi restrictions on U.N.
weapons inspections.
</P>
<P>
The United States is threatening to attack unless Iraq gives
the inspectors free access to all sites. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
