<HEADLINE> Anti-US Sentiments on Rise in Cairo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, February 21 (Xinhua) -- Arab journalists on Saturday
staged a sit-in and issued furious statements against the
U.S. government and its threat to bomb Baghdad to end the
Iraq-U.N. crisis over arms inspections.
</P>
<P>
During the four-hour sit-in organized by the Egyptian Press
Syndicate, journalists set fire to American and Israeli flags in
front of its premises.
</P>
<P>
They chanted slogans against what they called "arrogance and
double-standard in dealing with Israel and Iraq."
</P>
<P>
The Arab Affairs Committee at the organization also decided on
Saturday to declare a "Week of Solidarity" with the Iraqi people
soon.
</P>
<P>
This week will feature a photo exhibition and a video session
portraying the suffering of the Iraqi children, women and the
elderly caused by the embargo imposed more than seven years, the
Middle East News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
In tandem with the event, a number of meetings will be held by
those concerned with the cause of the Iraqi people.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Cairo-based Arab Journalists Federation issued a
statement here Saturday, appealing to the international community
for utmost efforts to avert a military strike against Iraq and to
show solidarity with the Iraqi people.
</P>
<P>
The federation criticized the U.S. policy for seeking to
convert the United Nations into a tool to serve its policies based
on "hegemony, arrogance and double standard."
</P>
<P>
"While the U.S. is amassing a huge military force to strike
Iraq for the alleged possession of biological weapons, it rejects
any attempt to discuss Israel's arsenal of weapons of mass
destruction," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
The statement urged Washington to re-consider its policies that
"raise tension in the region" and to respond to international and
Arab diplomacy aiming at reaching a peaceful settlement of the
crisis.
</P>
<P>
Washington has been speeding up its military buildup in the
Gulf in preparation for a strike if diplomatic moves fail to bring
an end to the crisis over weapons inspections.
</P>
<P>
U.N. Secretary General Kofi Annan arrived in Baghdad Friday in
a last-ditch effort to persuade Iraq to give arms inspectors free
and complete access to all sites suspected of hiding secret
weapons programs.
</P>
<P>
The past few days saw a surge of protests by students,
intellectuals and politicians against American military
muscle-flexing.
</P>
<P>
Although people differ on how much Iraqi President Saddam
Hussein is to blame for the crisis, there is a consensus of anger
against what they deem as America's "aggressive intentions."
</P>
<P>
According to a public opinion survey published by Al Arabi, the
mouthpiece of opposition Nasserist Democratic Party, 79 percent of
Egyptians polled are against any form of U.S. military action
against Iraq.
</P>
<P>
The survey also showed 61 percent believed that the aim of the
strike would be to support Israel and 75 percent called for an
Arab summit to discuss the issue. 
</P>
</TEXT>
