<HEADLINE> Three Former Zairean Generals Leave S. Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, February 21 (Xinhua) -- Three former Zairean
generals, whose extradition was demanded by the Kinshasa
government, have left South Africa for an unknown destination,
Reuters quoted sources as saying Friday.
</P>
<P>
The news agency said the three -- former defense minister
Mavua Mudima, former presidential guard commander Nzimbi Nzale
and former army chief of staff Baramoto Kpama -- left South
Africa last week by road.
</P>
<P>
The generals of late Zairean president Mobutu Sese Seko were
accused by Kinshasa of plotting to kill President Laurent Kabila,
whose forces overthrew Mobutu last May and renamed the country
the Democratic Republic of the Congo.
</P>
<P>
The generals, who had been living in South Africa since
Mobutu's fall, were arrested last December on charges of entering
the country with false documents. They were released later
without any charges by a Pretoria judge.
</P>
<P>
Reuters quoted senior security and military officers in
Kinshasa as saying that they were aware of the generals'
departure but had no knowledge of their destination.
</P>
<P>
"We know they have left South Africa. But we are still trying
to verify their new home of exile," a senior commander in
Kinshasa was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
"At least this ends our standoff with South Africa. Our job
now is to find out where these guys have gone because they are
always plotting against us," another source said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
