<HEADLINE> Iran Hopes Annan to End Iraqi Crisis Politically </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, February 21 (Xinhua) -- Iranian Foreign Minister Kamal
Kharrazi Saturday expressed the hope that the visit of U.N.
Secretary General Kofi Annan would lead to a political solution
to the ongoing Iraq-U.N. crisis over arms inspections.
</P>
<P>
According to the official news agency IRNA, Kharrazi told
visiting Omani Minister of State for Foreign Affairs Yousef Bin
Alawi Bin Abdullah that military operations should be replaced by
political understanding.
</P>
<P>
He said he hoped that cooperation between Baghdad and Annan
would lead to the implementation of the U.N. Security Council
resolutions and avert "any unfavorable event in Iraq as well as
the region."
</P>
<P>
Annan is currently in Baghdad to mediate a political solution
to the standoff between the U.N. and the Iraqi government over
arms inspections and to avoid a U.S. military strike on Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Despite Washington's continuous threat to attack Iraq, Tehran
believed that it was possible to solve the Iraqi issue through
Annan's mission.
</P>
<P>
As Iraq's neighbor and chairman of the Organization of the
Islamic Conference, Iran encouraged Annan to visit Iraq and said
it would actively contribute to finding a peaceful solution,
Kharrazi said.
</P>
<P>
Iran believes that resort to war will not be in the interests
of anyone, he added.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Omani official said that his country is also
interested in solving the crisis through peaceful means.
</P>
<P>
On the other hand, the two sides underlined the need for Iraq
to cooperate with the U.N chief to implement the U.N. Security
Council resolutions.
</P>
<P>
The Omani official arrived here earlier Saturday for a one-day
visit and left here for home after delivering a message from Omani
Sultan Qaboos Bin Said to Iranian President Mohammad Khatami.
</P>
</TEXT>
