<HEADLINE> Russia, Japan Sign Fishing Agreement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, February 21 (Xinhua) -- An intergovernment agreement on
fishing cooperation on the South Kuril islands was signed here
Saturday by Russian First Deputy Prime Minister Boris Nemtsov and
Japanese Foreign Minister Keydzo Obuti, according to the Interfax.
</P>
<P>
The two sides hoped that the agreement will promote bilateral
economic cooperation, there will be no more illegally fishing and
people will be able to work safely in the area.
</P>
<P>
The report said the agreement defines the areas and rules of
fishing for Japanese fishermen around the South Kurils on a
commercial basis and the control mechanism over the observation of
Japan's quotas.
</P>
<P>
It said that in 1998 Japanese fishermen are allowed to catch
about 2,300 tons of walleye pollack and raps and 120 tons of
octopuses in the area.
</P>
<P>
The agreement does not give any quotas for catching the
Kamchatka crab because its resources are exhausted, the report
said.
</P>
<P>
After almost three years of negotiations, Russia and Japan
reached in December 1997 a final agreement to sign an accord on
cooperation in fishing off the South Juril Islands.
</P>
<P>
The agreement is for the first time in about 50 years of the
Russia-Japanese dispute over whom they belong to to define rules
of cooperation in the area. 
</P>
</TEXT>
