<HEADLINE> Nigeria Denies Territorial Goal in W. Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, February 21 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria has said it has no
territorial ambitions in playing a leading role in peacekeeping
operations in west Africa.
</P>
<P>
With the belief that "we should do whatever we can to assist
our neighbors", Nigeria involved itself actively in peacekeeping
in both Liberia and Sierra Loene, said Nigeria's Chief of Defense
Staff Abdulsalam Abubakar.
</P>
<P>
The successful peacekeeping operations have put an end to the
seven-year civil war in Liberia and brought down the military
junta in Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
The achievements helped Nigeria's neighbors change their
previous resentment against it because they had realized that
Nigeria had no territorial goals, Abubakar said.
</P>
<P>
Abubakar, now on an official assignment in New York, said over
the weekend that Nigeria's involvement in west African affairs had
been guided by its concern for peace and tranquility in the
sub-region, the Nigeria News Agency reported on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
In Lagos on Friday, Chief of Navy Staff Okhai
Akhigbe also denied any imperialist motive in the foray into
Sierra Leone of the Nigerian-led west African peacekeeping force
known as ECOMOG, which last week ousted the junta.
</P>
<P>
"We do not have territorial ambition or any desire to dominate
any country within our sub-region," the officer said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
