<HEADLINE> Northern Ireland Army Experts Blow Up Belfast Car Bomb </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, February 21 (Xinhua) -- Northern Ireland army technical
officers carried out a controlled explosion on a car bomb in west
Belfast Saturday, reports said.
</P>
<P>
It was discovered near a black taxi at Norglen Parade in the
Turf Lodge area late in the morning.
</P>
<P>
The new discovery stepped up the strain on Northern Ireland
peace efforts after the suspension of Sinn Fein from negotiations
Friday and a huge blast outside a small town police station. Seven
police officers and four civilians were wounded by Friday night's
blast in the town of Moira near Belfast.
</P>
<P>
Sinn Fein, the political wing of the Irish Republican Army
(IRA), was expelled from the talks for two week until March 9 as a
punishment for the IRA's involvement in two killings last week.
</P>
<P>
So far no one has claimed responsibility for Friday night's
explosion. But Ronnie Flanagan, the province's police chief,
accused unidentified Republicans of the bomb attack in Moira.
</P>
<P>
"Obviously it is the work of Republican extremists. Exactly
what organization is responsible, it is too soon to say at this
stage," Flanagan told reporters.
</P>
<P>
Sinn Fein in turn accused pro-British Protestant extremists of
planting Saturday's bomb. Reports said the taxi with bombs inside
was owned by a former Republican prisoner who had been targeted
before.
</P>
<P>
Despite the two incidents in Northern Ireland over the past two
days, Sinn Fein leader Gerry Adams said the IRA cease-fire -- a
condition for Sinn Fein's admission to the talks -- remained
intact. 
</P>
</TEXT>
