<HEADLINE> African Leaders Determined on Lasting Solution to </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
(by Wang Shangzhi, Shi Guangzhou)
</P>
<P>
KAMPALA, February 21 (Xinhua) -- Leaders from east and central
African countries, in a communique published here Saturday, reaffirmed
their determination to find a lasting solution to the conflict in
Burundi.
</P>
<P>
During the one-day conference on Burundi, the leaders agreed
to continue to implement all previous decisions including those
concerning sanctions on the central African country.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the leaders pledged to review the sanctions if the
conditions matured, and an all-party talk was recommended under
the auspices of Julius Nyerere, the facilitator of the Burundi
peace process.
</P>
<P>
The sixth regional summit held in Kampala Saturday was
attended by heads of state and government from Uganda, Kenya,
Tanzania, Zambia, Ethiopia and Burundi.
</P>
<P>
Nyerere, Tanzania's former president, Salim Ahmed Salim,
Secretary General of the Organization of Africa Unity, and
representatives from Zimbabwe, Rwanda and the Democratic Republic
of Congo were also present at the meeting.
</P>
<P>
Pierre Buyoya, President of Burundi, briefed the conference on
the political situation in Burundi and various steps taken by his
government to meet the decisions made by the fifth summit held in
Dar-es-Salaam in September 1997.
</P>
<P>
After a review of the situation in Burundi, the leaders noted
that there was no significant improvement in the political
situation in the country and agreed that there is no alternative
to a negotiated solution to the problem in the central African
country.
</P>
<P>
Official trade links between Burundi and its neighbour
countries have been cut since the sanction was imposed in July
1996 to punish the coup that brought Buyoya to power.
</P>
<P>
Fighting in the mountainous country is still going on almost
every day. 
</P>
</TEXT>
