<HEADLINE> Annan Expects to Meet Saddam Sunday </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, February 21 (Xinhua) -- United Nations
Secretary-General Kofi Annan expected to meet Iraqi President
Saddam Hussein Sunday for talks on diplomatic solutions on the
Iraqi crisis, U.N. officials here said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
But the officials said that the U.N. chief, who arrived in
Baghdad Friday for a critical peace mission to avert the
threatened U.S. and British airstrikes against Iraq, could not set
the time of his meeting with the Iraqi leader.
</P>
<P>
Annan began his official meetings Saturday morning at the Iraqi
Foreign Ministry. Half of the three-hour morning session was
devoted to a private meeting between Annan and Iraqi Deputy Prime
Minister Tariq Aziz.
</P>
<P>
"We started well. It's not easy," Annan told reporters at the
state guest house where he is staying.
</P>
<P>
"We still have quite a lot of work to do, but had a good
meeting," he said of his morning talks with Iraqi leaders.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. secretary-general said he expected to get a document
and an agreement out of his weekend diplomacy in the Iraqi
capital.
</P>
<P>
Annan is scheduled to report his visit to the U.N. Security
Council Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Although Annan's trip to Baghdad was widely believed to be the
last-ditch effort to seek a peaceful solution to the weapons
inspection crisis in Iraq, France said Saturday that Anna's talks
in Baghdad may not be the last attempt.
</P>
<P>
French Foreign Minister Hubert Vedrine said that Annan's
mission could be a clear success or a total failure, but could
also produce a compromise which the Security Council would have to
accept or reject. 
</P>
</TEXT>
