<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bonn, Paris, Warsaw Pledge to Deepen Trilateral </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
POZNAN, Poland, February 21 (Xinhua) -- France, Germany and
Poland Saturday pledged to intensify trilateral cooperation after
a summit meeting of French President Jacques Chirac, his Polish
counterpart Alexander Kwasniewski and German Chancellor Helmut
Kohl.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press conference after the summit in the western
Pleit of PKnan, Kwasniewski said that the three countries had
agreed not only to continue their existing political and economic
cooperation, but also to promote cultural contacts among young
people of the three nations.
</P>
<P>
He also highlighted the historical significance of the summit,
which is the first one since the foreign ministers of three
countries started in 1991 in the eastern German city of Weimar the
so-called Weimar Triangle mechanism to conduct regular
consultations, and first of all to pave the way for Poland's
integration into the North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO) and
the European Union (EU).
</P>
<P>
The defense ministers of the three countries have also started
to meet regular meetings every year since 1994.
</P>
<P>
Kwasniewski said that experience gathered from the regular
trilateral contacts was very important for European integration.
</P>
<P>
Also speaking at the press conference, both Kohl and Chirac
stressed that Bonn and Paris want Poland to join NATO and the EU
as soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
Chirac also expressed the hope that trilateral cooperation
among Paris, Bonn and Warsaw could become a driving force behind
European integration in the future.
</P>
<P>
Poland was among the three Eastern European countries which was
invited to join NATO in 1999, which still needs approval by the
parliaments of all current NATO members.
</P>
<P>
It is also one of the five Eastern European countries with
which the EU is due to start membership negotiations at the end of
March this year.
</P>
<P>
Kohl told reporters that Germany and France would continue to
help Poland during the integration process, but he also stressed
that Poland should first of all make its own efforts to meet the
necessary conditions for joining the EU.
</P>
<P>
Answering a question about the upcoming summit between himself,
Chirac and Russian President Boris Yeltsin, Kohl stressed that the
summit was not meant to direct against anybody.
</P>
<P>
It was in the interests of Europe as well as the United States
to make all efforts to ensure that democracy and market economic
reforms would prevail in Russia at a time of dramatic changes,
Kohl said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
