<HEADLINE> Berger: Military Preparations Go Ahead Despite </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, February 21 (Xinhua) -- National Security Adviser
Sandy Berger said Saturday that U.S. military preparations are
proceeding without regard to U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan's
talks with Iraqi officials over settlement of the weapons
inspection crisis in Iraq.
</P>
<P>
"I would say that U.S. military preparations are proceeding
without regard to these talks," Berger said after meeting with
President Bill Clinton and his top foreign policy advisers for
more than 90 minutes in the Oval Office Saturday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
And his remarks to reporters came as hundreds of anti-war
demonstrators gathered in a park across the street from the White
House.
</P>
<P>
"Clearly whenever there is military action, it provokes and
evokes strong feelings on the part of many people," Berger said,
underscoring that the United States was going ahead with plans for
air strikes on Iraq despite Annan's last-ditch diplomatic mission.
</P>
<P>
Berger said Annan, in Baghdad meeting with the Iraqi officials,
has been charged with pressing two fundamental conditions to
ending the standoff over the weapons inspections: access to all
sites and total control of the inspection process by the U.N.
Special Commission (UNSCOM).
</P>
<P>
"There could be details that would not undermine those two
objectives that we would not object to," he added.
</P>
<P>
White House spokesman Mike McCurry said Saturday no signs are
evident that Iraqi President Saddam Hussein wants to resolve the
crisis "in a peaceful fashion."
</P>
<P>
"There continue to be provocative statements issued from
Baghdad and no indication of a complete willingness to resolve
this in a peaceful fashion," he said.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, the State Department issued a warning to Americans in
Iraq to "depart as soon as possible." The Pentagon also sent a
memo to U.S. news executives alerting them to potential dangers
that journalists could face in Iraq. 
</P>
