<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Urges More Health Care for Minorities </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, February 21 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
Saturday called for an end to the disparity in the health of the
country's minorities, who suffer from some diseases more than five
times the rate of white Americans.
</P>
<P>
In his weekly radio address, Clinton announced measures that
include spending 400 million dollars over five years in an effort
to improve the health of minorities.
</P>
<P>
Clinton said, "We must not be blind to the alarming fact that
too many Americans do not share in the fruits of our progress, and
nowhere are the divisions of race and ethnicity more sharply drawn
than in the health of our people."
</P>
<P>
He said infant mortality rates are twice as high for
African-Americans as for white Americans, and African-American men
suffer from heart disease at nearly twice the rates of whites.
</P>
<P>
African-Americans are more likely to die from breast cancer and
prostate cancer, and overall cancer fatalities are
disproportionately high among both Latinos and blacks, Clinton
said.
</P>
<P>
There are similar disparities among native Americans and some
Asian-Americans, he said.
</P>
<P>
Clinton said, "Research shows that overall all these groups are
less likely to be immunized against disease, less likely to be
routinely tested for cancer, less likely to get regular checkups."
</P>
<P>
The president's five-point plan includes a new outreach
campaign led by newly-confirmed Surgeon General Dr. David Satcher,
more than 400 million dollars to develop new approaches to address
racial and ethnic health disparities, a new foundation/public
sector collaboration to address disparities, more effective ways
to target existing federal programs to address health disparities,
and a national challenge to involve communities, foundations,
advocacy organizations, and businesses to develop ways to target
racial and ethnic health disparities. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
