<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-21 20:51 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkey Rejects UN Call to Open Border to Refugees </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, February 21 (Xinhua) -- Turkey on Saturday flatly
rejected an appeal by the United Nations to open its borders for
refugees fleeing a possible military strike against Iraq.
</P>
<P>
"It is impossible for us to let them in," Turkish Deputy Prime
Minister Bulent Ecevit was quoted by the semi-official Anatolia
News Agency as saying.
</P>
<P>
Ecevit's remark was in response to a call made last week by
U.N. High Commissioner for Refugees, requesting the neighboring
countries of Iraq not to shut their doors to the refugees.
</P>
<P>
It is widely believed that large numbers of Iraqi Kurds might
pour into southern Turkey if the U.S. troops launched a
large-scale military strike against Baghdad.
</P>
<P>
"But there is no need to concern," Ecevit said, "Turkey has the
capability to protect them just across its borders."
</P>
<P>
Turkish government forces have reportedly been deployed along
the Turkish-Iraqi borders in case of any emergency.
</P>
<P>
It was also said that some Turkish military and civilian
personnel had been sent to northern Iraq to establish "observation
posts" for a possible flood of refugees.
</P>
<P>
Turkish Foreign Ministry said earlier that Ankara was ready to
provide necessary humanitarian aid to those Iraqis who might surge
toward the border in the event of a U.S. military operation.
</P>
<P>
Local media reports had said that Turkish government intended
to build a "security zone" in northern Iraq aimed at curbing the
infiltration of militants of the Kurdish Workers' Party (PKK),
which is outlawed in Turkey for their separatist struggle. The
reports, however, were denied by Ankara.
</P>
<P>
The PKK has been fighting a 13-year-old war against the Turkish
government for an independent state in southeastern Turkey.
</P>
<P>
As a neighbor of Iraq, Turkey has called on Iraqi President
Saddam Hussein to comply fully with the relevant U.N. Security
Council resolutions to avert a U.S. military attack.
</P>
<P>
Turkish leaders has time and again said that Turkey does not
want to see a new war breaks out in this region, stressing that
more efforts should be made to find a diplomatic solution to the
current crisis over U.N. weapons inspections in Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Turkey suffered huge economic losses as a result of the
U.N. sanctions imposed on Iraq in the wake of the 1991 Gulf War,
which drove Saddam's troops out of Kuwait. 
</P>
</TEXT>
