<HEADLINE> Annan Holds Lengthy Talks With Iraqi Leaders </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, February 21 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General
Kofi Annan held lengthy talks Saturday night local time with Iraqi
Deputy Prime Minister Tareq Aziz in an intense effort to seek a
diplomatic way out of the U.S.-Iraq standoff over the weapons
inspection, informed U.N. sources here said.
</P>
<P>
The meeting, the second round of its kind in the day, lasted
three hours, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
U.N. officials accompanying the U.N. chief's mission told
reporters that they were optimistic about the outcome of Annan's
mediation in Baghdad.
</P>
<P>
Annan, who flew in to the Iraqi capital Friday, is struggling
to avert threatened U.S. and British military strikes against
Iraq.
</P>
<P>
He is trying to persuade Baghdad to grant U.N. arms inspectors
unrestricted access to eight Iraqi "presidential sites." He has
made clear to Iraqi leaders that any accord would have to include
two key elements.
</P>
<P>
These were full compliance with U.N. resolutions and no
dilution of the role of the U.N. Special Commission charged with
scrapping prohibited Iraqi weapons of mass destruction.
</P>
<P>
Annan told reporters after his three-hour morning talks with
the Iraqi leaders that they "started well."
</P>
<P>
Asked if the talks had been substantive, the U.N. chief said,
"Yes, that's why I say I'm rather optimistic."
</P>
<P>
He said he hoped there would be an agreement from his talks to
open all suspected weapons sites. 
</P>
