<HEADLINE> Khamenei: Iran for Brotherly Ties With Neighbors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, February 21 (Xinhua) -- Iran's supreme leader
Ayatollah Ali Khamenei said Saturday that the Iranian nation
seeks no war, but brotherly relations with regional countries.
</P>
<P>
According to the Iranian official news agency IRNA, Khamenei
made the remark in a meeting with a group of residents of Iranian
islands in the Persian Gulf in Bandar Abbas, capital of the
southern province of Hormozgan.
</P>
<P>
"We feel brotherly towards the nations and countries of the
region and insist that they feel and value our brotherhood," he
said, adding that "Islamic Iran seeks security and exaltation for
all Muslim states in the region."
</P>
<P>
He said that exaltation of the Muslim world would be possible
only through unity, which is the "secret of the victories of the
Iranian nation."
</P>
<P>
This was yet another signal of goodwill the Iranian leadership
sent to the Gulf Arab neighbors. Former Iranian President Hashemi
Rafsanjani is on a landmark visit to Saudi Arabia as part of the
effort to improve relations with Gulf states.
</P>
<P>
Rafsanjani, who chairs Iran's powerful State Expediency
Council, is accompanied on the visit by ministers of agriculture,
oil and labor and Majlis (parliament) members to discuss issues of
the Muslim world and cooperation among regional countries.
</P>
<P>
Relations between Iran and the Gulf states cooled down after
Iran's Islamic Revolution in 1979 but warmed up last year
following the election of the moderate President Mohammad Khatami,
who underlined friendly relations with regional countries.
</P>
<P>
During his speech, Khamenei attacked foreign military presence
in the region, saying that "enemies of Islam" have always tried to
portray the region as insecure or render it as such in order to
legitimize their presence in the Gulf.
</P>
<P>
However, he stressed, Iran manages, through its might, to
achieve and maintain security for itself and seeks security for
all the regional states. 
</P>
</TEXT>
