<HEADLINE> House Republicans Sue Against Census Sampling </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, February 21 (Xinhua) -- Republicans in the U.S.
House of Representatives have filed a lawsuit seeking to stop the
Census Bureau from using statistical sampling as part of the
population count in 2000.
</P>
<P>
The suit, filed Friday in the U.S. District Court, alleges that
sampling "is prohibited by the Constitution, which requires that
an `actual enumeration' be obtained by `counting the whole number
of persons in each state.'"
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, in a letter House Speaker Newt Gingrich, a
Republican, urged President Bill Clinton to join the Republicans
in seeking a prompt ruling on the merits of the suit, rather than
resort to "technical justiciability arguments" that could delay a
decision until after it is too late to affect the census.
</P>
<P>
But Commerce Department general counsel Andrew Pincus said the
administration is obligated to challenge the suit if it falls
outside the jurisdiction of the courts, and that the
constitutional issue is being weighed by attorneys.
</P>
<P>
However, Pincus said, "We look forward to proving the legality
of sampling in court."
</P>
<P>
The legal action is the latest development in a politically
charged attempt by the Republicans to force the administration to
abandon sampling in the Census 2000.
</P>
<P>
Census Bureau officials want to use statistical sampling to
adjust for expected errors in the head count, particularly as it
affects minorities.
</P>
<P>
But Republicans argued that sampling is unconstitutional.
Republicans reportedly fear that if sampling is used, their
majority in the House could be affected when census figures are
used to redraw legislative district lines in several states before
the 2002 elections. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
