<HEADLINE> Iraq Unable to Increase Oil Output: Diplomat </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, February 21 (Xinhua) -- An Iraqi diplomat said Saturday
that Baghdad is unable to increase oil output before its
infrastructure is repaired, the Middle East News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
"At present Iraq can not sell more than 4 billion dollars worth
of oil (every six months) due to damages made to its refineries
and oil fields by the long embargo imposed on Baghdad," Iraq's
permanent representative to the Arab League Nabil Nejm was quoted
as saying.
</P>
<P>
"If oilfields, refineries and pumps were not repaired, Iraq
could not increase its oil sales," he added.
</P>
<P>
In a bid to ease the humanitarian situation in Iraq, the
U.N. Security Council voted Friday to allow Baghdad to more than
double the amount of oil it can sell under the U.N. oil-for-food
plan.
</P>
<P>
Under the resolution passed unanimously by the 15-member
council, Iraq is allowed to sell up to 5.2 billion dollars worth
of oil every six months, from the present 2 billion.
</P>
<P>
"We do not reject the draft but Iraq simply does not possess
the ability to increase oil pumping operations," Nejm explained.
</P>
<P>
The oil-for-food deal, began in December l996, permits Iraq to
use part the proceeds to buy food and medicines for its 22 million
people suffering from crippling sanctions imposed after Iraq's
1990 invasion of Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
Baghdad first rejected raising the ceiling of the oil-for-food
deal, demanding instead the embargo be removed altogether.
However, the sanctions can only be lifted after Iraq is certified
to have eliminated its weapons of mass destruction.
</P>
<P>
According to the Iraqi diplomat, Baghdad is also objecting to
the fact that the U.N., rather than Iraqi government, is taking
charge of the allocation of the oil revenues.
</P>
<P>
"According to Security Council resolution 987, Iraq should
prepare the plan of proceeds distribution, but the U.N. Sanctions
Committee and the U.S. seem to dodge this resolution," he added.
</P>
<P>
The new oil-for-food proposal can not be implemented until Iraq
submits a distribution plan to U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan,
is in Baghdad to find a peaceful solution to Iraq's standoff with
the U.N. over weapons inspections. 
</P>
</TEXT>
