<HEADLINE> U.S. Striking Plan Against Iraq Approved Four Weeks Ago </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, February 21 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
and his top military and foreign policy advisers have approved an
intense, four-day, round-the-clock bombardment, The New York Times
said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The plan, aimed at undermining the Iraqi military apparatus and
diminishing its ability to produce and deliver biological and
chemical weapons, was passed at a meeting chaired by Clinton on
January 24, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
Pentagon planners have named the military campaign "Desert
Thunder."
</P>
<P>
U.S. officials said that the planning was framed by several
considerations, including the assumption that Iraq would never
give the inspectors the full access they need to do their jobs.
</P>
<P>
The bombing salvos would pound Iraq's air defense, fighter
planes, command posts, missile factories, Republican Guard
compounds, intelligence headquarters and sites that can produce
chemicals, according to the paper.
</P>
<P>
There are no immediate comments available about the report from
the Clinton administration.
</P>
<P>
The administration said Saturday that it hopes U.N.
Secretary-General Kofi Annan's last-ditch diplomatic mission to
Iraq succeeds, but "U.S. military preparations are proceeding
without regard to these talks."
</P>
<P>
The warning came from Clinton's National Security Adviser Sandy
Berger after a 90-minute meeting with the president and his top
foreign policy advisers in the Oval Office Saturday afternoon.
</P>
