<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, February 21 (Xinhua) -- Iranian Foreign Ministry
Saturday summoned the Pakistani ambassador to Iran Javid
Hussein, lodging strong protest to the killing of two Iranian
engineers in Karachi, Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
Iranian Deputy Foreign Minister Mohsen Aminzadeh handed over a
note of protest to hussein, strongly criticizing the the Pakistani
government and called on Islamabad to clarify the matter.
</P>
<P>
The Iranian official news agency IRNA quoted Aminzadeh as
saying that terrorist acts had claimed lives of Iranians in
different parts of Pakistan during the recent years due to the
fact that the Pakistani government officials had failed to
seriously pursue and punish the terrorists.
</P>
<P>
The two Iranian engineers named as Ali Mohammad Habibzadeh
and Morteza Adibzadeh in charge of constructing a bridge
project in Karachi were gunned down Saturday afternoon by
unidentified gunmen. But no reports were available here so far
about details about the killing.
</P>
<P>
Aminzadeh warned the relations between Tehran and Islamabad
would be gravely affected if the Pakistani government failed to
take severe measures against the terrorists.
</P>
<P>
He also expressed concern that Pakistan has been transformed
into "an insecure state for the Iranians," calling on the
Pakistani government to closely review their policy in order
to counter such terrorist acts of the enemies of the two
nations.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Tehran radio reported that the Iranian Majlis
Speaker Ali Akbar Nateq Nouri Saturday also condemned the
killing of the two Iranians in Pakistan, calling on Islamabad
to take serious measures to fight against terrorists in the
country.
</P>
<P>
Last September, five Iranian air force trainees were killed by
unidentified gunmen in Pakistan, damaging the relations between
the two countries. Reports said that so far the Pakistani
authorities failed to identify the real killers in that
incident. 
