</P>
<P>
The official Iraqi News Agency in a brief dispatch described
the talks over the inspection of Iraqi presidential sites by
U.N. weapons experts as "difficult," but said discussions
nontheless continued.
</P>
<P>
The critical circumstances have prompted Iraqi President Saddam
Hussein to chair a joint meeting of the Revolution Command Council
and the Command of Socialist Arab Baath Party earlier Saturday
night to study the Annan-Aziz talks.
</P>
<P>
The third round of Annan-Aziz talks, which started at 11
p.m. local time (2100 GMT), are now under way, and officials here
have no idea when and how they will end.
</P>
<P>
After their first round Saturday afternoon, a U.N. spokesman
said Annan-Aziz talks were "constructive," but refused to disclose
any details.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. chief said he was "rather optimistic" about striking a
deal with Baghdad giving U.N. weapons inspectors' free and
unrestricted access of all suspected sites to avert a military
confrontation in the region.
</P>
<P>
Annan arrived here Friday evening in a last-ditch effort to
find a diplomatic solution to the Iraqi-U.N. standoff over the
inspection of presidential sites suspected of concealing secret
illegal weapon programs. 
