<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Economic Growth May Go on Through 2000: Poll </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, February 21 (Xinhua) -- Most of U.S. business leaders
think the current economic expansion may continue through the year
2000, a recent poll shows.
</P>
<P>
They believe that low inflation, strong productivity and steady
Federal Reserve (Fed) policy deserve the credit, said the
Investor's Business Daily Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The poll was conducted this month by the Investor's Business
Daily and the Technometrica Institute of Policy.
</P>
<P>
The 101 business leaders responding to the poll represent U.S.
top companies, based on their earnings' growth instead of size.
</P>
<P>
Seventy-eight percent of the respondents saw low inflation as a
driving force of growth. Consumer prices edged up 2.3 percent in
1997, down from a 3 percent hike in 1996.
</P>
<P>
On the interest rate front, the outlook for continued low
inflation has prevented the Fed from raising the rate for 11
months. The current rate of 5.5 percent was set last March when
0.25 percentage point was added.
</P>
<P>
Ongoing falls in commodity prices and cheap imports from Asia
are expected to keep the Fed on hold, many believe.
</P>
<P>
As productivity has been on the rise, though at a lower pace
last year, weak productivity was ranked as the seventh threat to
the economic growth, after higher taxes, Fed policies, government
regulation, inflation, decline in the stock market and rising
wages.
</P>
<P>
Jitters about higher taxes were eased when the federal budget
deficit was shrinking.
</P>
<P>
Under the circumstances, over two thirds of respondents said
they have planned to increase employment over the next six months
and 88 percent of them look forward to growing profits and are
ready to invest more in new technology. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
