<HEADLINE> Asia Could Recover From Crisis: G-7 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, February 21 (Xinhua) -- The Group of Seven said
Saturday that Asia could recover from the current financial crisis
through adoption and vigorous pursuit of significant and
far-reaching reforms.
</P>
<P>
Finance ministers and central bankers from the G-7 agreed in a
communique that reform in Asia should ensure the effects of the
financial crisis on world growth were "manageable" this year.
</P>
<P>
"Where countries pursue the necessary reforms, the prospects of
a return of confidence top global investors and a resumption of
vigorous growth in the medium term are good," the G-7 said.
</P>
<P>
But the communique used stern words for Japan, saying its
outlook for growth was weak and that fiscal stimulus was needed to
boost a stubbornly sluggish economy.
</P>
<P>
In response to the criticism, Japan insisted that its European
and Norther American partners simply misunderstood the program for
growth already underway in Japan.
</P>
<P>
As far as Europe is concerned, the G-7 said that growth was
below potential in Germany, France and Italy and that they needed
"significant" structural reforms to cut unemployment.
</P>
<P>
In the United States, Britain and Canada, the G-7 took comfort
from the fact that inflation was weaker than expected given their
strong growth records.
</P>
<P>
Looking ahead, the communique stressed that one clear lesson to
date was that emerging and transition countries which strengthen
their economic policies help avoid the consequences of contagion.
</P>
<P>
In the interest of the longer term proper functioning of the
financial markets, it was essential for the private sector to play
its role in resolving crises, it added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
