<HEADLINE> Living Buddha Wishes for National Unity and Ethnic Consolidation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LANZHOU, February 22 (Xinhua) -- The Living Buddha Jamyang
Losang Jigme Tubdain Qoigyi Nyima, the head of Lapuleng Monastery
in China's Gansu Province, said that the aspiration and duty of
every Tibetan is to safeguard national unity, strengthen ethnic
consolidation, and oppose splittist activities.
</P>
<P>
He has just been elected deputy to the Ninth National People's
Congress which is to hold its first annual session in March.
</P>
<P>
Lapuleng Monastery is one of the largest Tibetan monasteries in
China and attracts many people from Gansu and Qinghai provinces
and the Tibet Autonomous Region.
</P>
<P>
Living Buddha Jamyang, who is 50, was a Standing Committee
member of the National Committee of the Chinese People's Political
Consultative Conference (CPPCC) for 20 years before he was made an
NPC deputy from Gansu Province.
</P>
<P>
He said that in the past he helped manage state affairs by
participating in political affairs in the CPPCC, but can now
directly exercise the power of the state as an NPC deputy. For
many years, he has made an effort to guard the unification of the
motherland. In the coming NPC session in Beijing, he will continue
to make an appeal for national unity and ethnic consolidation, he
said.
</P>
<P>
The government has a policy of freedom in religious belief and
protects normal religious activities, he says, so yearly religious
services have been successful. Tens of thousands of Buddhists
took part in services this year.
</P>
<P>
Living Buddha Jamyang just presided over religious activities
lasting for 15 days in the first month of the lunar calendar, which
were attended by Tibetan, Mongolian and han Buddhists. " Many
people came a long way through mountains on horses or donkeys, but
now highways lead to the monastery and people are coming by bus,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese government believes that all ethnic groups are
equal and provides autonomy in areas inhabited by ethnic groups,
to ensure their position in the country's political affairs, he
said.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
