<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-22 15:26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ma'an Returns to Calm After Two Riots </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, February 22 (Xinhua) -- Jordan has tightened security in
the southern city of Ma'an in an effort to prevent recurrence of
riots, which over the last two days have left one dead and 10
others injured.
</P>
<P>
The security force issued a statement Sunday saying that
security and calm have been fully restored in the city, which
witnessed two pro-Iraqi and anti-U.S. riots breaking out Friday
and Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Local people were defying a government ban on march and
movement and taking to the streets to express their support for
Iraq and vent their anger over a threatened U.S. military strike
against Baghdad.
</P>
<P>
The demonstrations turned into riots and clashes with the
police, killing one man and injuring two on Friday, and leaving
eight more wounded on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The security force statement said that as part of the measures
to curb further violence, all the unlicensed weapons in the city
would be confiscated. A demonstrator shot to the sky with a
sub-machine gun during Saturday's riot, residents said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, local parliamentary deputies were being contacted by
the police to spot organizers of the consecutive riots, the
statement added.
</P>
<P>
There is a heavier presence of police force in the city, where
destroyed automatic cash-dispensing machines beside the main
streets could still be seen and electricity remains out of reach
in some parts - power lines were cut off during the riots.
</P>
<P>
King Hussein went to Ma'an on Saturday after the riot was
stopped to persuade the residents not to help "infiltrators,
vandalists and elements" endanger national security.
</P>
<P>
Jordanian popular support for Iraqi people remained strong,
despite strained Jordanian-Iraqi ties and Amman's much closer
links with Washington since it signed a peace treaty with Israel
in 1994.
</P>
<P>
The first rally this month expressing solidarity with Iraqi
people erupted more than a week ago when over 1,000 prayers took
to the streets around the famous Al-Hussein Mosque in downtown
Amman.
</P>
<P>
Washington has threatened military attacks to force Iraqi
compliance with the U.N. Security Council resolutions and the free
and full access by U.N. weapons inspectors to the "off-limits"
presidential palaces suspected of hiding prohibited weapons.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
