<DOCNO> XIE19980222.0058 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sandra Volker Top Winner at World Cup Swimming in Hong Kong </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, February 22 (Xinhua) -- With an impressive
performance which earned her four gold medals, German swimmer
Sandra Volker overshadowed Alexandre Popov of Russia as the most
valuable individual at the 1998 FINA World Cup Swiming Meet which
closed here on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Volker's performance helped the German team to a top-ranked 13
gold medals on the final medal tally. The Germans also took four
silver and two bronze medals to total at 19.
</P>
<P>
Australia, team event winners at last year's tournament here,
were edged to the second place on the medal table, with a medal
credit of 4-4-3 to total at 11.
</P>
<P>
Denmark also obtained four golds, but with only three silver
medals to make a medal tally of seven.
</P>
<P>
They were followed by Ukraine with three golds, Sweden, Russia
and Japan each with two, and Britain, Belarus, Croatia, and
Belgium, one for each.
</P>
<P>
With two gold medals from the opening day's competitions,
24-year-old Volker continued her triumphant advance on Sunday to
take the 100 meters freestyle and 100 meters backstroke events.
</P>
<P>
"I'm happy with the victries as this is the first competition
since the World Championships in Perth," she said.
</P>
<P>
Volker said she expected her teammates and herself do better in
the Beijing leg of the World Cup series, where she competes in the
very same events as here.
</P>
<P>
But the German star declined to predict how fast she could be
in the third leg there.
</P>
<P>
"I'm going to take a long rest after the World Cup series since
I had been competing ever since the Olympic Games (in Atlanta),"
she said.
</P>
<P>
Volker said she had no idea what would be her next competition
and whether she would come back to Hong Kong for the short-course
World Championships in 1999.
</P>
<P>
Her male teammate and world breaststroke record holder Mark
Warnecke further boosted the team moral when he took his second
gold at the event on Sunday. With little difficulty, he won the
men's 100-meter breaststroke final, to add on his victory in the
50 meters breaststroek on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Popov won his second gold medal at the current short-course
tournament here, with a clocking of 22.08 seconds in the men's 50
meters freestyle final on Sunday. He keeps the event's world
record of 21.50 seconds set in 1994.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese team, with members out of form after the recent
holidays during the traditional Chinese Spring Festival, showed up
in a below-par performance. They just took three silver, six
bronze medals to total at nine. 
</P>
</TEXT>
