<HEADLINE> Annan on Verge of Breakthrough: UN Spokesman </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, February 22 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General Kofi
Annan is on the verge of a breakthrough to resolve the crisis over
weapons inspections in Iraq, his spokesman said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The announcement was made after Annan, who arrived here Friday
on a last-ditch mission, held a three-hour meeting with Iraqi
President Saddam Hussein.
</P>
<P>
"As a result of those discussions he feels he is on the verge
of a breakthrough," U.N. spokesman, Fred Eckhard, said at a press
conference here.
</P>
<P>
He said that "Substantial progress was made today, we feel that
a deal is within reach."
</P>
<P>
Replying to a question, he added that Annan "certainly hopes
that he can reach agreement tonight or tomorrow morning."
</P>
<P>
Declining to elaborate on the details of the talks, the
spokesman said that the U.N. chief and his team are expected to
hold further talks with Iraqi Deputy Prime Minister Tariq Aziz
Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
A written agreement will be drafted Sunday night but the deal
is not finished, Eckhard said, adding that Annan is expected to
leave Baghdad early Monday afternoon. 
</P>
</TEXT>
