<HEADLINE> UAE Urges US to Be "Justice" On Iraq Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, February 22 (Xinhua) -- United Arab Emirates (UAE)
President Sheikh Zayed bin Sultan al Nahyan said Sunday that the
United States should "be characterized by justice" in dealing
with the current crisis between Iraq and the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
While urging the U.S. to avert to resort to the logic of force
against Iraq, the UAE president said "the United States is a
major world power, and its policies should be characterized by
justice and by providing support to those things which are
right."
</P>
<P>
"A (U.S.-led) military action against Iraq is something
rejected by us. It is hateful and repugnant," he said in a
statement issued following the departure of visiting Yemeni
President Ali Abdullah Saleh.
</P>
<P>
"It would cause endless problems and would also damage the
relations of friendship between the West and the Arab and Muslim
peoples," he said.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. and Britain have threatened to launch attacks on Iraq
if U.N. Secretary General Kofi Annan fails in his last-ditch
mission in Baghdad to persuade Baghdad to comply with U.N.
resolutions related to dismantling weapons of mass destruction.
</P>
<P>
The UAE has openly opposed a military solution to the crisis
triggered by Iraq's refusal to allow U.N. arms inspectors free
access to presidential sites suspected of hiding biological
or chemical weapons.
</P>
<P>
The UAE president stressed in his statement that he "appeals to
the international community...to exert its efforts in all
sincerity to avert military showdown...so that the U.S. will not
accelerate its resort to military action."
</P>
<P>
He also rejected U.S. warnings that Iraq formed a potential
threat to the Gulf region.
</P>
<P>
"There is no threat from Iraq toward its neighbors," he said.
</P>
<P>
On the different Arab stands toward the Iraq crisis, the
president complained "no solidarity" in this field.
</P>
<P>
"There is no mutual solidarity among the Arab states at
present...There is no indication of Arab mediation in the
crisis," he said.
</P>
<P>
"It is important there should be a unifying of our ranks. We
should work with sincerity to re-establish Arab solidarity,
especially at this critical time," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
