<HEADLINE> 2ndadd: Iraq Calls Saddam, Annan Meeting "Positive" </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, February 22 (Xinhua)-- Iraqi President Saddam
Hussein's meeting Sunday with U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan
was held in a "positive atmosphere," said an Iraqi official
spokesman.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said Saddam and Annan had a two-hour private
meeting.
</P>
<P>
He said Iraqi Deputy Premier Tariq Aziz and Foreign Minister
Saeed Sahhaf were present when Saddam received Annan and his
delegation.
</P>
<P>
Annan held four rounds of "difficult" talks with Aziz in the
last one and half days before having a meeting with Saddam in the
presidential Sunday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
Diplomatic sources here said Annan and Aziz made progress in
their talks, but they did not reach an agreement on the time
limit on the inspection of Iraqi presidential sites by U.N. arms
inspectors.
</P>
<P>
Annan had said he would meet with Saddam to clarify with him a
number of thorny issues before he went to meet Saddam.
</P>
<P>
Annan is reportedly going to meet Aziz again later Sunday on
the remaining obstacles blocking the way to an agreement on the
U.N. inspections of the presidential sites in Iraq which have been
suspected of hiding weapons of mass destruction.
</P>
<P>
The United States has threatened to take military actions to
force Iraq to grant unfettered and unrestricted access to
U.N. arms inspectors to all sites suspected of hiding weapons of
mass destruction if Annan fails to persuade Iraq to back down.
</P>
