<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Second Phase of Indian General Elections Ends </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, February 22 (Xinhua) -- The second phase of the
general elections to the 12th Lower House of Parliament in India's
nine states and the Union Territory of Pondicherry off the coast
of Bay Bengal ended Sunday evening.
</P>
<P>
Barring sporadic incidents of violence that left five people
dead and more than 30 others injured, the polling in the country
passed off peacefully for 183 Parliamentary seats out of 543 in
the House.
</P>
<P>
The turnout was reportedly moderate to fairly heavy in the nine
states and the Union Territory of Pondicherry with 45 to 50
percent of voters casting their ballots.
</P>
<P>
According to the election schedule announced by the Election
Commission, the current general elections are divided into four
main phases of February 16, 22, 28 and March 7.
</P>
<P>
The 11th Lower House of Parliament, which was elected in
April-May 1996, was dissolved by President R. K. Narayanan on
December 4 last year as no political party could muster enough
support to form the next government after the Gujral government
resigned on November 28.
</P>
<P>
The fate of 405 members out of 543 MPs has been sealed in the
two phases of elections. Another 136 MPs will be elected in the
third and fourth phases of elections on February 28 and March 7.
</P>
<P>
Polling in Mandi and Ladakh for two seats in northern India has
been postponed to June on account of cold weather conditions.
</P>
<P>
Security has been beefed up in all the 183 constituencies on
Sunday in view of violence-marred first phase of polls on February
16 when massive rigging and killing were reported in the country,
especially in Bihar State of eastern India.
</P>
<P>
Four people were killed in Bihar and one was killed in Orissa
State of eastern India in the second phase of general elections on
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Two Bihar ministers were detained following disturbing polling
process in the state. This is the first time that the senior
officials have been detained in the elections since February 16.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
