<HEADLINE> Israeli Jets Raid Hezbollah Positions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, February 22 (Xinhua)--Israeli Air force (IAF) jet
fighters raided Sunday morning several Hezbollah positions in
South Lebanon in retaliation against the Hezbollah's Saturday
attacks on South Lebanese Army (SLA), Israel Radio said.
</P>
<P>
The IAF jet fighters launched their air raids on the
Hazbollah positions around the Soujud area in the northeast of
the security zone and all the fighters returned safely, the
Radio quoted the IAF as saying.
</P>
<P>
But there were no reports of casualties on the side of
Hezbollah, it added.
</P>
<P>
Several squads of Hezbollah gunmen on Saturday launched an
attack against the SLA position in Soujud under the cover of
heavy mortar fire. The Attackers advanced to within a few hundred
meters of the Soujud outpost of the SLA and opened fire with
light machine guns and automatic rifles, according to IDF.
</P>
<P>
The IDF and SLA fired back with machine guns, rifles,
mortars and artillery, forcing the attackers to retreat, and
there were no IDF or SLA casualties.
</P>
<P>
Some Hezbollah may have been hit in the fighting which
lasted more than an hour, IDF said.
</P>
<P>
The attacks on Saturday followed four days of relative
quiet in the security zone which coincided with the longest-ever
session of the Grapes of Wrath Monitoring Committee.
</P>
<P>
The five-nation Committee began its discussions on Tuesday into
complaints from Israel over mortar fire last week at Kiryat
Shmona and Shiheen village in northern Israel.
</P>
<P>
There were no casualties in Kiryat Shmona, five people were
wounded in Shiheen.
</P>
<P>
The monitors have recognized Israel's complaint regarding the
mortars which fell in Kiryat Shmona, despite strong denials by
the Lebanese delegation.
</P>
<P>
The committee determined that the incident was a clear breach
of the understanding between the two sides in April 1996. 
</P>
</TEXT>
