<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-22 13:40 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AL Optimistic Over Peaceful Solution to Iraqi </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, February 22 (Xinhua) -- Arab League (AL) Secretary
General Esmat Abdel-Meguid Sunday voiced optimism over a possible
peaceful solution to the Iraq-U.N. crisis over weapons inspection,
the Middle East News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
"There is a general tendency to solve this crisis peacefully
and avoid a military strike against Baghdad, a matter which is
strongly supported by the Arab League," he said.
</P>
<P>
While calling upon Iraq to implement the U.N. Security Council
resolutions, he urged Washington to give room to peaceful means
to solve the crisis, which was sparked off by Iraq's refusal to
grant the U.N. arms inspectors unfettered access.
</P>
<P>
The AL chief also attributed the current Iraq-U.N. standoff
"behavior and statements made by international arms inspectors'
chief Richard Butler."
</P>
<P>
Abdel-Meguid also noted the flexibility shown by the
U.S. government recently in seeking a political way out.
</P>
<P>
"The U.S. approval of the current mission by U.N. Secretary
General Kofi Annan in Baghdad mirrored the American side's
readiness to seek a political settlement to this standoff," he
said.
</P>
<P>
After a day of "difficult negotiations," the U.N. chief Sunday
met with Iraqi President Saddam Hussein to try to reach an
agreement on arms inspections to avert a U.S. military strike.
</P>
<P>
In a related development, U.S. Assistant Secretary of State for
Middle East Affairs Martin Indyk reiterated that Annan's visit is
fully supported by the Security Council's five permanent member
states, including the U.S..
</P>
<P>
"The visit represents a last-ditch attempt of the ongoing
diplomatic efforts to persuade Saddam Hussein to abide by the
international legitimacy resolutions," he said in an interview
with Egyptian daily Al Ahram Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. diplomat also ruled out a widespread concern that the
Middle East peace process is being overshadowed by the current
crisis with Iraq.
</P>
<P>
"We do not want to delay the peace process. We deal with the
peace process in the same time we tackle the crisis with Saddam
Hussein," he added.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian-Israeli peace talks have been stranded since
last March over Israel's settlement building and dragged into
deeper recession following two suicide bombing attacks in
Jerusalem in last July and September.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. has failed to broker an end to the peace deadlock when
it gets involved in the U.N-Iraq standoff since November over
Baghdad's refusal to let the U.N. Special Commission (UNSCOM in
charge of scrapping Iraqi weapons of mass destruction) to enter
its presidential sites.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. has been reinforcing its military presence in the Gulf
in preparation for a strike if Baghdad continues to bar
"presidential sites" to U.N. arms inspectors, a central dispute of
the current crisis. 
</P>
</TEXT>
