<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Heavy Ion Accelerator Installed in Northwest China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LANZHOU, February 22 (Xinhua) -- Chinese scientists have scored
new progress in research into radioactive ion beams, as a heavy
ion accelerator went into operation in this capital city of
northwest China's Gansu Province recently.
</P>
<P>
Established by the Institute of Modern Physics under the
Chinese Academy of Sciences (CAS), the accelerator has passed
appraisal by nuclear physicists recently.
</P>
<P>
Construction of the accelerator began in 1995. It underwent
more than 2,100 hours of stable operation before it was given the
go-ahead. Scientists have obtained more than 30 kinds of nuclide
from it.
</P>
<P>
The accelerator features all the major advantages of similar
installations in other countries, Chinese scientists said.
</P>
<P>
Research into radioactive beams is an advanced topic in nuclear
physics which helps scientists to learn more about the microcosmos
inside the atomic nucleus. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
