<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hebei Becomes China's Second Largest Vegetable Producer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHIJIAZHUANG, February 22 (Xinhua) -- North China's Hebei
province last year produced 34.2 million tons of vegetables,
becoming the second largest vegetable producer of China, after
east China's Shandong province.
</P>
<P>
Some 25 million farmers in Hebei benefited from vegetable
growing.
</P>
<P>
The vegetable growing area in Hebei reached 723,000 hectares in
1997, with 213,600 hectares in greenhouses, 10 times that of 1992.
</P>
<P>
The provincial government and vegetable growers in
Hebei invest a combined 10 billion yuan annually in vegetable
production, starting from 1993.
</P>
<P>
With the advantage of neighboring Beijing and Tianjin
municipalities, Hebei has set up four vegetable production and
sales bases in the counties around Beijing and Tianjin.
</P>
<P>
Vegetables from Hebei now cover 36 percent of the vegetable
wholesale markets in Beijing. Hebei has also established vegetable
wholesale relations with over 20 cities. It sells some 18 million
tons of vegetables a year to other Chinese provinces.
</P>
<P>
Hebei has also adjusted its vegetable growing structure,
shifting from quantity to quality by improving growing techniques.
</P>
<P>
The province now grows 130 types of fine brand vegetables, of
which are eight state-level and 30 province-level brand name
vegetables.
</P>
<P>
At the end of 1997, 84 percent of vegetables produced in the
province entered the market.
</P>
<P>
The province has also formed 52 vegetable processing
enterprises with an annual capacity of 420,000 tons.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
