<HEADLINE> Iraqi Parliament Speaker Calls on U.N. to Stop </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, February 22 (Xinhua) -- Iraqi National Assembly
(parliament) Speaker Sadoun Hammadi called on the U.N. Security
Council Sunday to stop the United States from launching a
military attack on Iraq, the Iraqi News Agency INA said.
</P>
<P>
The speaker denied as "a lie" the U.S. allegation that there
are banned weapons in presidential sites, saying the allegation
was designed to create a pretext for taking military actions
against Iraq, according to INA.
</P>
<P>
He said Iraq has implemented all relevant U.N. resolutions on
disarmament in Iraq and cooperated with U.N. arms inspectors, who
have conducted around 2,500 visits to suspected sites.
</P>
<P>
Hammadi made the remarks at an assembly meeting, which decided
to present a note to members of the U.N. Security Council, urging
them to stop a possible U.S. military aggression against Iraq.
</P>
<P>
The note said 42 international organizations stand by Iraq and
oppose to the use of force in solving the standoff between Iraq
and the United States over U.N. weapons inspection.
</P>
<P>
The assembly also called for the implementation of
U.N. Security Council resolution 687 and the lifting of economic
sanctions imposed on Iraq for more than seven years.
</P>
<P>
The assembly met as U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan concluded
another round of talks with Iraqi Deputy Premier Tariq Aziz Sunday
morning and left to meet with Iraqi President Saddam Hussein in the
presidential palace here. 
</P>
</TEXT>
