<HEADLINE> Annan Ends Talks with Saddam </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, February 22 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General Kofi
Annan ended his talks with Iraqi President Saddam Hussein and the U.N.
chief will make an announcement on the outcomes of his talks with the
Iraqi leadership, well-informed U.N. sources said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Annan, who held three rounds of talks lasting eight hours Saturday
in the Iraqi capital of Baghdad, held talks with Saddam for about two
hours, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
Their talks were focused on one remaining "significant" sticking
point in phrasing a document that Annan could take back to the U.N.
Security Council in New York.
</P>
<P>
The sources said that the remaining unresolved issue was the
time limit for U.N. arm inspectors to Iraqi sites suspected of
housing chemical or biological weapons. 
</P>
