<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Open First Round-the-Clock AIDS Hotline </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 22 (Xinhua) -- A leading anti-AIDS
organization in China plans to open the country's first 24-hour
hotline as a new channel for the public to acquire knowledge about
AIDS (acquired immune deficiency syndrome).
</P>
<P>
The hotline's host will be a computer-controlled
voice-simulator for which telephone callers only need to press
buttons to get answers, according to the China Association for the
Control of AIDS and Sexually-Transmitted Diseases (STDs).
</P>
<P>
Almost all of China's provinces, autonomous regions and
municipalities have similar hotlines, which are staffed by medical
professionals, but they only operate during certain hours.
</P>
<P>
"All relevant topics may be discussed between callers and the
hotline staff, such as homosexuality, the nature of AIDS, and how
to avoid and cure STDs,'' said a lady surnamed Wang, who works as
a volunteer at an AIDS hotline opened by the Health Education
Institute under the Ministry of Health.
</P>
<P>
Experts estimate that China has at least 150,000 people
infected by HIV -- the AIDS virus. They blame the epidemic on
prostitution and drug abuse.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry of Health is working on a plan to effectively
control HIV infection among drug users by year 2000, while keeping
the annual increase rate of STDs under 15 percent.
</P>
<P>
Furthermore, the number of HIV cases will not surpass 1.5
million by the year 2010, according to the plan.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
