<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ethiopian, Russian Win Hong Kong New Airport Marathon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, February 22 (Xinhua) -- It was neither the most
favored Ethiopian Turbo Tumo nor Australia's lone participant
Patrick Carroll that outshone others.
</P>
<P>
The crown of the 1998 Hong Kong Standard Chartered New Airport
Marathon was taken away here on Sunday by Tumo's teammate Bellay
Wolashe, who got one toe hurt midway.
</P>
<P>
With that bleeding toe, the 28-year-old Wolashe clocked two
hours 13 minutes nine seconds at the finish line for the men's
event, the first marathon race for him this year.
</P>
<P>
The time, lower than his personal best of 2:10.57, set in 1993
in France, is a new record for Hong Kong international marathon.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak Hussein from Kenya won the second place in 2:13.52 and
Tanzanian Onesmo Ludago finished third in 2:14.16.
</P>
<P>
The women's top honor also went to a 28-year-old athlete.
Russian college student of physical culture Alina Ivanova won in
2:39.26, followed by Ethiopia's Senalt Teklu in 2:44.00 and
Tanzanian Maimuna Margwe in 2:56.46.
</P>
<P>
A newly-bought pair of training shoes cost Wolashe the chance
to improve his personal best. One of his left toes was badly hurt
and began bleeding after some 25 kilometers' run.
</P>
<P>
But the Ethiopian prison police in his home town Addis Ababa
managed to take over the lead from Tumo at the 35km mark and he
never let any chance for others in the rest of the race.
</P>
<P>
"If not under such a humid weather, I should have run faster,"
he said after the victory.
</P>
<P>
He praised the flat course, especially the closing section on
the runway of the new airport and hoped to come back next year to
give a better show.
</P>
<P>
Tumo, 27, finished a disappointing sixth.
</P>
<P>
Russian winner Ivanova, 28, had revealed at a pre-race press
conference that she had been training in Florida, the United
States, for the past month. But she did not owe her victory to
this factor. "It was very hot there," she said.
</P>
<P>
It did not seem to bother her that she failed to improve her
personal best. "To run on the runway of a new airport made me very
excited and the triumph made the feeling even better," she said.
</P>
<P>
Local runners Lam Weng Hei and Ng Lai Chu won the men's and
women's titles in the separate 10 kilometers races on the
airport's runway, clocking 34 minutes 50 seconds and 38 minutes
and eight seconds respectively.
</P>
<P>
The new airport is to be named as Hong Kong International
Airport, when it is opened for business on July 6 this year.
</P>
<P>
An impressive field with 1,200 entries for the marathon and
another massive batch of 5,000 runners and 18 wheelchair athletes
made Sunday's event the biggest ever athletic gathering in Hong
Kong. 
</P>
</TEXT>
