<HEADLINE> China To Strengthen Anti-doping Measures in Swimming </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 22 (Xinhua) -- Shi Tianshu, vice chairman of
the Chinese Swimming Association (CSA), emphasized that China will
strengthen its anti-doping measures as the 1998 FINA Diving Grand
Prix is to be opened here on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Shi said on Sunday that China will continuously cooperate with
FINA, the world swimming ruling body, and other nations to make
this sport free of drugs.
</P>
<P>
The CSA is determined to take more effective actions to tackle
the drug-taking offences, such as anti-doping education and a
drug-free written guarantee from each participant prior to each
event, and the association is duly to resort to more strict
penalties than the rules of FINA to punish any offender, the
Chinese sports official said.
</P>
<P>
Sun Shuwei, Barcelona Olympic champion and winner of the
synchronized event in the World Swimming Championships last month,
will skip the event due to tiredness, together with Guo Jingjing,
runner-up of the women's 3-meter springboard in Perth.
</P>
<P>
South Korea has abandoned its trip to China as it is said to
compete in the national diving championship at the time, leaving
only five countries for the Diving Grand Prix in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
Beijing is the second leg of the FINA Diving Grand Prix
series. 
</P>
</TEXT>
