<HEADLINE> Emergency Medical Assistance Available for Chinese Travelers Abroad </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 22 (Xinhua) -- An emergency medical
assistance service has been introduced for Chinese who travel
overseas, as more and more Chinese people nowadays are planning
trips abroad.
</P>
<P>
The service is jointly provided by the France-based Europ
Assistance and China International Travel Service (CITS), the
standard-bearer of China's booming tourism industry.
</P>
<P>
"We believe the service will have a huge market potential, even
though it is still a new concept in China," said Stephanie
Olivier, chief representative of Europ Assistance in Beijing, a
global provider of medical assistance services for over 30 years.
</P>
<P>
Europ Assistance has established a worldwide network of local
agents, report centers and hospitals. Medical assistance teams
swing into action as soon as a customer calls for help, Olivier
said.
</P>
<P>
The company has seen a sluggish increase in the number of
customers since the service was launched last year.
</P>
<P>
"It is understandable, because many travelers don't think
they'll need it," said Zhu Jingyan, manager of CITS Overseas
Economic Cooperation, the domestic agent for Europ Assistance.
</P>
<P>
"But I believe more and more people, especially elderly
tourists, will choose the service in future," Zhu said.
</P>
<P>
The number of Chinese people travelling abroad has been
climbing continuously in recent years. A total of 2.56 million
Chinese citizens went abroad for personal reasons last year, a
rise of seven percent over the figure for 1996, according to
official statistics.
</P>
<P>
Among them, more than 1.06 million were tourists, a rise of 5.6
percent over 1996.  
</P>
</TEXT>
