<HEADLINE> 2 State Ministers Detained in India's Elections </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, February 22 (Xinhua) -- Two ministers of Bihar State
in eastern India were detained by police for creating disturbances
during the second phase of general elections on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Reports reaching here said that incidents of violence have
claimed four lives and caused injuries to many in Bihar State.
</P>
<P>
Bihar Energy Minister B. Prasad was kept under "house arrest"
while State Minister for Welfare S. Sinha was detained at
Samastipur allegedly for "violating the model code of conduct and
creating disturbances during polling."
</P>
<P>
This is the first time that senior officials have been detained
since the first phase of elections to the 12th Lower House of
Parliament were held on February 16.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, polling in Mandi and Ladakh two seats in northern
India has been postponed to June on account of adverse weather
conditions.
</P>
<P>
Over 200 million voters will decide the electoral fortunes of
over 1,600 candidates including prime ministerial candidate of the
Bharatiya Janata Party (BJP) Atal Behari Vajpayee Sunday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
