<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mammoth Exhibition to Commemorate Lei Feng (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 22 (Xinhua) -- China's younger generation,
born and raised in the period of reform, opening-up and market
economy, will soon get an opportunity to learn about the life and
achievements of Lei Feng, the country's leading model of altruism.
</P>
<P>
Approved by the Publicity Department of the Communist Party of
China (CPC) Central Committee, an exhibition titled "The
Everlasting Spirit of Lei Feng" is to be held in the Museum of the
Chinese Revolution in downtown Beijing.
</P>
<P>
The museum, located on the eastern side of Tiananmen Square, is
regarded as one of the country's most prestigious sites for
exhibitions. At the moment it is hosting a memorial exhibition on
the 100th anniversary of the birth of China's late Premier Zhou
Enlai.
</P>
<P>
The organizers of the Lei Feng exhibition, from northeast
China's Liaoning Province, claim that the exhibition will be the
biggest one dedicated to Lei Feng since the 1960s, when China's
late Chairman Mao Zedong personally prompted a national campaign
to learn from this model soldier of the People's Liberation Army
(PLA).
</P>
<P>
A truck driver with the PLA's Shenyang Military Area Command,
stationed in Liaoning Province, Lei Feng took great pleasure in
helping others and doing good deeds for society. After his tragic
death at the age of 22 in an accident in 1962 he was held up as a
model of the new socialist man, and publicity about his life and
contributions was spread throughout the country.
</P>
<P>
"Lei Feng is the only hero in China who has been honored with
inscriptions from New China's three generations of leaders," said
Tian Jingxiang, deputy director of the city People's Congress of
Fushun, where Lei Feng was based when he served in the army.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980222.0105 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mammoth Exhibition to Commemorate Lei Feng (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
In 1963 Mao Zedong wrote an inscription urging the whole
country to "Learn From Comrade Lei Feng". Deng Xiaoping and Jiang
Zemin, top Chinese leaders after Mao, wrote their inscriptions in
the 1980s and 1990s.
</P>
<P>
According to Tian, the exhibition will be held in the North
Hall of the museum, which has a floor space of 1,500 sq m, with
178 photographs and 200 objects relating to Lei Feng on display.
</P>
<P>
The organizers have also invited eyewitnesses to major events
in Lei Feng's life to serve as guides and answer questions of
curious young visitors, he added.
</P>
<P>
He said that middle-aged and old people, who were quite
familiar with Lei Feng in their younger days, would also be
interested in the exhibition, for 20 photographs and 27 objects
are on display for the first time.
</P>
<P>
They include a story and a poem written by Lei Feng in his own
handwriting, and a notebook in which he recorded all his donations.
</P>
<P>
"The visitors will also be able to hear the recorded voice of
Lei Feng recollecting his own miserable childhood before
Liberation in 1949,'' said Tian. He added that it was recorded in
Fushun in 1961.
</P>
<P>
The organizers plan to open the exhibition February 27 and run
it through March 27. It will then tour all the other major Chinese
cities. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
