<DOCNO> XIE19980222.0106 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Blackout Looms in Nigerian Capital </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, February 22 (Xinhua) -- Residents of Abuja, Nigeria's
capital, who used to take for granted stable supply of water and
electricity, are beginning to feel the degeneration of power
supply.
</P>
<P>
Abuja has only one source of electricity supply, which is the
132 kv power line from Shiroro dam, some 100 km away in the
north.
</P>
<P>
But the line has been over-stretched, a development that has
led to instability of supply to communities in the federal
capital territory (FCT), an administrative division with the same
status as the 36 states under the federal government.
</P>
<P>
The pressure of serious electricity supply situation has
forced the National Electric Power Authority (NEPA) in the FCT to
connecting electricity to new buildings since last October.
</P>
<P>
The trend has heightened anxiety that unless the 132 kv power
line is beefed up urgently, the electricity supply position to
the FCT could snap, leaving the territory in darkness.
</P>
<P>
However, it is feared that NEPA's refusal to grant
applications for meters could slow down the tempo of construction
activities in the FCT, which has remained high since the movement
of the federal government from Lagos to Abuja in December 1991.
</P>
<P>
To solve the problem, the line should be upgraded to 330 kv to
cater to the fast pace of development in the FCT, according to
NEPA officials.
</P>
<P>
The project is expected to cost 10 billion Naira (about 125
million U.S. Dollars), according to the Sunday Champion newspaper
today.
</P>
<P>
But the government in ~? year's budget only plans to
allocate two billion Naira (about 25 million Dollars) for the
project. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
