<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Africa Expects Good Maize, Wheat Harvest </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, February 22 (Xinhua) -- South Africa is likely
to have good harvest of maize and wheat in the 1998/99 season,
the National Crop Estimates Committee said at the weekend.
</P>
<P>
The first official maize and wheat crop estimates for the
season suggest that earlier estimates of El Nino's impact on
crops were exaggerated. Good crops should give the economy a
slight boost this year, the committee said.
</P>
<P>
The 1998/99 commercial maize crop, to start in May, would be
6.86 million tons -- 2.8 million tons of yellow maize and 4.06
tons of white one, the committee said.
</P>
<P>
Last season's bumper crop amounted 8.5 millions tons.
</P>
<P>
The committee raised its total maize acreage estimate on the
crop to 3.1 million hectares from the 2.81 million announced last
month.
</P>
<P>
If this estimate proves to be correct, it would meet domestic
consumption needs of between six and seven million tons,
agricultural department officials said.
</P>
<P>
The good rains during the past few months are likely to boost
South Africa's economy by 1.5 percent in the fourth quarter last
year from 0.3 percent in the first quarter, some economists
predicted.
</P>
<P>
Local press quoted economist Peter Worthington as saying that
the figures were an improvement on October estimates when El Nino
was expected to shave one percentage point off this year's GDP
growth rate.
</P>
<P>
"May be the hit will be only about 0.3 or 0.4 percentage
points, depending on the degree to which farmers have substituted
other crops for maize in anticipation of a bad drought,"
Worthington said.
</P>
<P>
South African economists expect economic growth of about two
percent this year, a figure which could now move up to 2.3
percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
