major English newspaper in Hong Kong showed that an overwhelming
majority of Hong Kong people back the first budget of the Hong
Kong Special Administrative Region presented by Financial
Secretary Donald Tsang.
</P>
<P>
In an exclusive poll commissioned by the Sunday Morning Post,
the weekend edition of the South China Morning Post, 90 percent of
respondents were satisfied with Tsang's fiscal blueprint for
1998-99, which he delivered at the Provisional Legislative Council
on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Lower tax rates and higher allowances were among the budget
features most warmly welcomed by respondents, with 92 percent
giving the changes their backing, according to the result of the
poll, which was published Sunday by the newspaper.
</P>
<P>
Bigger relief for dependent parents and grandparents ranked
second, with 91 percent of those questioned in favor.
</P>
<P>
About 84 percent of the respondents approved of the increased
expenditure on education, while 80 percent hailed the new mortgage
tax allowance, the newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
Almost half of the respondents believed Tsang had struck the
right balance between caution and stimulation in the face of the
Asian economic crisis, according to the newspaper.
</P>
<P>
The survey of 449 people was conducted on Wednesday and
Thursday, immediately after Tsang announced his financial plan.
</P>
