<HEADLINE> 4 People Killed in Poll-Related Violence </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, February 22 (Xinhua) -- At least four people were
killed and several others injured in the second phase of the
general elections to elect 183 MPs out of 543 members in nine
States and the Union Territory of Pondicherry off the coast of Bay
Bengal on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Among the four killed, three of them were in Bihar State of
Eastern India. The three people were killed in a clash between
supporters of two rival parties in Bihar's Sitamarhi and Barh
areas. Another one was a policeman who was shot dead in Koraput
constituency in Orissa State by outlawed people's war group which
had given a poll boycott call.
</P>
<P>
A series of explosions were reported from Deoghati and Thathan
areas in Hajipur and Vaishali constituencies in Bihar in which 10
people were injured.
</P>
<P>
Till 1500 hours (local time) about 30 percent of polling had
been recorded in 183 Parliamentary constituencies. In West Bengal,
an estimated 45 percent of votes were cast, the highest in the
country.
</P>
<P>
The first phase of elections were held on February 16. Another
136 seats will be elected in the third and fourth phases of
elections on February 28 and March 7.
</P>
<P>
Polling in Mandi and Ladakh two seats in northern India has
been postponed to June on account of adverse weather conditions.
</P>
<P>
Over 200 million voters will decide the electoral fortunes of
over 1,600 candidates including prime ministerial candidate of the
Bharatiya Janata Party (BJP) Atal Behari Vajpayee Sunday. 
</P>
