<HEADLINE> More Crime Cases Recorded in 1997 in Malaysia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, February 22 (Xinhua) -- Crime cases in Malaysia
increased by 37.85 percent in 1997 compared to those in 1996, the
Malaysian national news agency Bernama reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The number of crime cases rose from 87,902 in 1996 to 121,176
last year, Bernama said quoting Federal Crime Investigation
Department Director Yaacob Amin.
</P>
<P>
The increase by the percentage or by 33,274 cases last year was
much higher compared to an increase of 6,681 cases or 8.23 percent
in 1996 from the 81,221 cases in 1995.
</P>
<P>
The director said property crime topped the list last year with
104,257 cases, an increase by 28,695 cases or 37.98 percent over
those in 1996, and the other 16,919 cases involved violent crimes
which recorded an increase of 4,579 cases or 37.11 percent
compared to 12,340 cases in 1996 and 10,623 cases in 1995.
</P>
<P>
Yaacob said police had solved 17,824 cases or 17 percent of the
property crime with the arrest of 15,350 suspects.
</P>
<P>
"For the violent crimes, 7,916 cases have been solved with the
arrest of 7,226 suspects," he was quoted as saying. 
</P>
</TEXT>
