<HEADLINE> Lebanon Strives to Stabilize Financial Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, February 22 (Xinhua) -- The Lebanese Central Bank has
pumped 350 million U.S. dollars to stabilize the financial market,
a local radio reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Bank sources were quoted by the Voice of the People radio as
saying that the Central Bank was forced to make the intervention
last week to meet a sharp rise of demand for the dollar.
</P>
<P>
The sources attributed the rise to reports on Lebanese economic
situations presented by two international economic rating agencies
early this month, which they said exerted negative influence on
Lebanon's financial market.
</P>
<P>
The reports of the Standard and Poor and the Fiche IBCA have
downgraded Lebanon's credit rating from neutral to negative in the
view of its current difficult economic situations.
</P>
<P>
According to the reports, Lebanon may face a financial crisis
if the government does not take measures to curb the huge budget
deficit.
</P>
<P>
Last year, Lebanon's deficit rose by 59 percent, 22 percentage
points more than that outlined in the budget.
</P>
<P>
The 1998 budget set the deficit at no more than 42 percent, but
the deficit in January still broke the ceiling, reaching 45
percent. 
</P>
