<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Weather, Records, Medals and Marijuana Form Nagano Olympics  By Xinhua s portswriter Zhou Jie, Liang Xiyi </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAGANO, Japan, February 22 (Xinhua) -- Weather, records, medals and
marijuana. That was the 1998 Nagano Olympic Winter Games.
</P>
<P>
When the curtain of the 18th Winter Olympics dropped down and the
Olympic flame faded out on Sunday, many believed that the games was a
success, though it could not be compared with Lillehammer.
</P>
<P>
Before the games began, many concerns came to the weather and
weather had really become a trouble-maker to the organizers in the
first 13 days.
</P>
<P>
Since the first day of the games, weather had been playing havoc on
many competition sites. Wind, snow, fog and rain washed out Alpine
skiing events in six complete days.
</P>
<P>
The organizers had to compete against weather and arranged three
Alpine events in a single day, the most in winter Olympic history when
blue sky appeared.
</P>
<P>
For sure, the games was not the best ever in history when the
organizers failed to have IOC president Juan Antonio Samaranch's
traditional accolade.
</P>
<P>
However, it could be certain that this was the biggest ever in
winter Olympic history.
</P>
<P>
More than 2,300 athletes from 72 countries and regions took part in
the 16-day games, which featured 68 events in 14 sports, including
three new ones -- women's ice hockey, snowboarding and curling.
</P>
<P>
Germany, third in medal standing at last Olympic Winter Games in
Lillehamer, regained its leading status with 12 golds, nine silvers
and eight bronzes.
</P>
<P>
Norway, second in Lillehammer, remained runners-up with 10-10-5.
Russia, top finisher four years ago, was third in 9-5-3.
</P>
<P>
Athletes from China, Asia's sports power, did not display a
performance in Nagano as in Atlanta. For the sixth consecutive winter
Olymics, the Chinese athletes failed to grab a gold.
</P>
<P>
However, they had made some improvement in competition, if that was
a kind of progress. Chinese skaters and skiiers collected six silvers
and two bronze in Nagano, two medals more than the total they bagged
in their previous five appearance.
</P>
<P>
During the two-week games, the last in this century, many great
moments occured to be remembered.
</P>
<P>
In speed skating ice rink, five world records have been set by
skaters from the Netherlands, Norway and Germany, all of whom were
armed with slap skates.
</P>
<P>
Dutch speed skating trio, one of them racing for Belgium, deserved
a special mention. The three skaters, donning top-secret rubber
strips, lowered the world record three times in the men's 5,000
meters.
</P>
<P>
In the women's 5,000m distance, German Marianne Timmer and Gunda
Niemann-Stirnemann twice broke the world mark which had been held for
four years by Niemann-Stirnemann.
</P>
<P>
Another speed skater, Hiroyasu Shimizu, won Japan and Asia's first
gold medal with a world-beating run in the 500 meters sprint.
</P>
<P>
Two world records fell in short track speed skating in the events
of women's 3,000m relay and 1,000m sprint.
</P>
<P>
The most spectacular was when Austria's Hermann Maier crashed out
of the men's downhill as Alpine skiing's big race finally went ahead
on Friday 13th.
</P>
<P>
Maier, overall World Cup leader, crashed and broke two protective
safety nets after losing grip on a turn which ended up claiming 13
racers.
</P>
<P>
But two days later, he recovered from the crash and geared up to
win the giant slalom. The ex-brick layer collected two titles at the
games.
</P>
<P>
Italian ski legend Alberto Tomba had his great career ended in
disappointment. After he crashed in the giant slalom, he finished
17th in the first run of the slalom, which gave him no hope to win a
medal in Nagano, thus smashing his dream to win a medal in four
consecutive Olympics.
</P>
<P>
Norwegian cross-country skier Bjorn Daehlie became the brightest
star in the games. On snow hills and slopes, he had not only to
compete against rivals in Nagano, but also race against those in
history. In the final, he defeated all. After spearheading the
Norwegian team to win the men's 4x10km relay, he became the most
successful Winter Games athlete in history with seven golds.
</P>
<P>
On the closing day of the games, Daehlie continued his power to win
the 50km free skiing, adding his Olympic gold total to eight.
</P>
<P>
Ice hockey professionals made their debut at winter Olympics, stars
from the NHL made the competition a "Dream Tournament", in which Czech
Republic became a surprising winner with a 1-0 victory over Russia on
game's closing day.
</P>
<P>
Marijuana became a story in the games. When snowboarding announced
its arrival in the games, it also began to challenge the power of the
International Olympic Committee (IOC).
</P>
<P>
Canadian snowboarder Ross Rebagliati, who won the men's giant
slalom, was disqualified by the IOC and was told to hand back his gold
medal after he tested positive for traces of marijuana.
</P>
<P>
Rebagliati, who said he gave up pot since last April and had
inhaled second-hand smoke, was reinstated by the Court of Arbitration
for Sports which ruled that there was no legal ground for his
disqualification.
</P>
<P>
The IOC could do nothing but to obey the rule. The world sports
governing body, with its drugs rules in disarray, decided to set up a
top-level taskforce to formulate a policy on marijuana and other
"social drugs, " so as to have a unified code till the year 2,000,
when the next Olympic Summer Games is held in Sydney.
</P>
<P>
Transportation and language had been headache for many attending
the games. The Japanese organizers became flexible to arrange the
transportation to meet demands, but not enough. Most volunteers have
been ready to help foreign press and visitors, but they could do
little with difficulties in communication.
</P>
<P>
The Salt Lake City Organizing Committee, which will host the next
Winter Olympics in 2002, stayed in Nagano for three weeks to learn for
experience. They promised everything would be ready at that time.
</P>
<P>
It is definitely certain that there would be no language barrier in
Salt Lake City. But for transportation, who knows?  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980222.0123 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-22 08:59 </DATE_TIME>
