<HEADLINE> Kuwait Urges Baghdad to Accept UN Resolutions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, February 22 (Xinhua) -- Kuwait Crown Prince and
Prime Minister Sheikh Saad Al-Abdullah Al-Salem Al-Sabah urged
Iraq to accept unconditionally all the U.N. Security Council
resolutions to avoid a perilous situation for its people.
</P>
<P>
Sheikh Saad's remarks, which coincided the U.N. General
Secretary Annan's good offices in Baghdad, were made Saturday
night after attending an open session of Kuwaiti National
Assembly, according to local press Sunday.
</P>
<P>
He said that Iraqi President Saddam Hussein must "see
reason and act pragmatically for the sake of the helpless
and impoverished Iraqi people," adding that "Saddam must
implement all U.N. resolutions, without exception."
</P>
<P>
He said this is the last chance for Saddam, referring Annan's
talks in Baghdad aimed at ending the current Iraq-U.N. stand-off
through diplomatic means.
</P>
<P>
Annan held lengthy talks with Iraqi Deputy Prime Minister
Tareq Aziz in Baghdad Saturday to try to avert a U.S. military
strike and said he was optimistic that an agreement with Iraqi
government would be reached. He will hold talks with Iraqi
President Saddam Hussein at noon Sunday.
</P>
<P>
President Saddam backed down in a previous crisis over arms
inspections in 1993 after American air strikes, whereas a swift
U.S. military buildup and threats made him withdraw troops he had
moved toward the Kuwaiti border in 1995.
</P>
<P>
As the talks were going on, the U.S. President Bill Clinton,
having already approved a plan "Desert Thunder" for massive air
strikes on Iraq, met his top security advisers including Secretary
of State Madelaine Albright in the White House Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. has assembled a strike force of over 30 ships and 300
warplanes in the Gulf and the plan was reportedly foreseeing four
days of round-the-clock strikes which would target Iraq's
military infrastructures. 
</P>
