<HEADLINE> Poverty Elimination Project Launched in Tanzania </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, February 22 (Xinhua) -- The Tanzanian
government has launched a project aimed at helping youth and
women groups in the campaign of eliminating poverty across the
country.
</P>
<P>
The three-year project, known as Community-based Initiatives
for Poverty Eradication, is financed by the United Nations
Development Program (UNDP) with 877,300 U.S. Dollars, Sunday News
reported.
</P>
<P>
The National Project Coordinator, Joel Mwakitalu, said at a
seminar in Kibaha Saturday that the project will provide advocacy
education and training to the community-based organizations
(CBOs) so that they can help the poor learn how to eradicate
poverty.
</P>
<P>
He said the project is a continuation of the other two
projects, Domestic Development Services (DDS) and Partners in
Development Program (PDP), both of which have helped women and
youths in different productive activities.
</P>
<P>
The main purpose of the project is to help the beneficiaries
especially in the villages who have already shown interest in
escaping poverty to work harder after receiving education and
training, Mwakitalu explained.
</P>
<P>
He said the project will first start in the poorest four
regions in the country -- Coast, Dodoma, Kigoma and Lindi, and
then extend to other regions.
</P>
<P>
The Permanent Secretary in the Ministry of Labor and Youth
Development, Abubakar Rajab, also attended the two-day seminar.
</P>
</TEXT>
