<HEADLINE> Sri Lankans Asked Not to Go to Kuwait for Jobs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
COLOMBO, February 22 (Xinhua) -- The Foreign Employment Board
of Sri Lanka has asked local people who applied for employment in
Kuwait not to go to that country in view of a pending war in the
region.
</P>
<P>
Sri Lankan employees have been requested not to leave for
Kuwait with immediate effect, the TNL Radio Station reported
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The decision followed a request by Sri Lanka's counselor in
Kuwait due to the increasing tension between Iraq and the United
States, which has threatened to stage massive military strikes
against the Middle East nation, the radio said.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. has asked all its citizens working in Kuwait to
return home. However, many other countries, including Sri Lanka,
are yet to make a similar decision.
</P>
<P>
Many Sri Lankans are working in the Middle East as laborers or
housemaids.
</P>
<P>
Sri Lanka on Saturday voiced its support for a peaceful
political solution to the crisis over weapons inspection in Iraq.
</P>
<P>
The Foreign Affairs Ministry issued a statement on the
situation in Iraq, saying any military action would gravely affect
the people in Iraq and Sri Lanka therefore welcomes the diplomatic
efforts of United Nations Secretary-General Kofi Annan.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. chief is currently in Iraq holding talks with Iraqi
leaders. 
</P>
</TEXT>
