<HEADLINE> Kenya to Send Team to Europe for Tourism </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, February 22 (Xinhua) -- Tourism Minister Henry
Kosegey announced in Mombasa Saturday that a promotion team would
be sent to Europe next week to market Kenya as one of the best
tourists' destination in Africa.
</P>
<P>
The local weekly paper Sunday Standard quoted the minister as
saying that the team would visit BIT Fair in Milan, Italy, and
other tourism fairs in Germany, France, Britain and Sweden.
</P>
<P>
Kosegey said that his ministry would aggressively market this
East African country and improve its image abroad, especially in
Europe.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that his ministry is set to embark on a major
project of repairing roads, clearing garbage, increasing security
and improving water and power supply to boost tourism in Kenya.
</P>
<P>
The minister blamed the decline of kenya's tourism industry on
the negative publicity abroad by the foreign media and the
breakdown of the country's infrastructure.
</P>
<P>
He said, "let's not start pointing fingers over who is to
blame for the fall in tourism. The government and the private
sector must quickly come up with immediate solutions to save the
industry from collapse."
</P>
<P>
The Sunday Standard featured a front-page story entitled "Top
Industry Faces Collapse", saying that thousands of Kenyans face
an economically difficult future as one of the country's top
mass-employer industries struggles to survive the negative
effects of natural and man-made tragedies.
</P>
<P>
The paper said that kenya's tourism which is the country's
number one foreign exchange earner was undergoing "the worst
times since independence in 1963".
</P>
<P>
In 1994, Kenya attracted some 850,000 tourists with the
tourism industry earning the country 28 billion Kenyan Shillings
and four years later the number of tourists declined to about
60,000 with the bed occupancy currently being between 30 to 50
percent.
</P>
<P>
Local analysts attributed the decline of the country's tourism
to the stinking mounds of uncollected rubbish everywhere, badly
damaged roads, insecurity and violence, water and power
shortages, and harassment by beach boys.
</P>
<P>
In order to boost tourism industry, the paper said in its
comment Sunday, "we must put our house in order first". 
</P>
</TEXT>
