<HEADLINE> House Break-ins Increase in Zambia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, February 22 (Xinhua) -- Up to 55 percent of Zambian
households experienced break-ins and robbery in the past one year
with 58 percent of the incidents occurring during the day, Sunday
Times paper reported.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted a study by the Central Statistics Office as
reporting that up to 47 percent of households had their members
physically assaulted with weapons being used in 39 percent of the
cases.
</P>
<P>
The study attributed the increased cases to the worsening
poverty in the country.
</P>
<P>
The most frequently stolen items were clothes and kitchenware
in urban areas, accounting for 36 and 31 percent respectively.
</P>
<P>
In rural areas, the most frequently stolen items were food
crops and poultry, accounting for 27 and 26 percent.
</P>
<P>
Money and electronic appliances such as radios accounted for
at least 19 percent of the stolen items in urban areas while in
rural areas these figures stand at three percent.
</P>
<P>
The farming community was the hardest hit, accounting for
between 15 and 21 percent of the total cases.
</P>
<P>
The highest proportion of break-ins were recorded in Eastern
province which accounted for 21 percent with Central province
next at 18 percent followed by the Southern and Luapula provinces
which both had 17 percent.
</P>
<P>
Frauds and swindles accounted for at least four percent of the
total reported number of crimes with the Northern and Luapula
provinces recording the highest number of victims at seven and
five percent respectively. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
