<DOCNO> XIE19980222.0138 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Czech Republic Wins Men's Ice Hockey </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAGANO, Japan, February 22 (Xinhua) -- The Czech Republic claimed
the last gold medal of the 18th Olympic Winter Games on Sunday when
they defeated Russia 1-0 in the men's ice hockey final.
</P>
<P>
The lone goal was scored by Petr Svoboda in the third and last
period.
</P>
<P>
During the first period, both teams played tight man-to-man
defense, holding each other to few passes and clear shot-on-goal
attempts.
</P>
<P>
In the 19th minute of play, Jaromir Jagr took a hefty body check by
Russia's Alexei Zhitnik putting him on the bench holding an orange
towel to his face.
</P>
<P>
But the dominating forward was back out on the ice early in the
next period and nearly scored at 10:19 but the puck ricocheted off the
goal post.
</P>
<P>
The Czech Republic re-grouped during the break, coming back on to
the ice playing a more effective passing game against their opponents.
</P>
<P>
The deadlock ended at 48:08 when Svoboda salmmed a slapshot past
Russian goalie Mikhail Shtalenkov for the first and only goal of the
game.
</P>
<P>
Coming off of a face-off, Svoboda stayed near the blue line and was
fed the puck from Pavel Patera and Libor Prochazka.
</P>
<P>
The Russian team, attempting to level the score, pulled their
goalie in the final seconds of the game but did not succeed in marking
the board.
</P>
<P>
In the play-off for the bronze medal Saturday, Finland beat Canada
3-2. 
</P>
</TEXT>
