<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenyan Moslems Slam US Plans of Raiding Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, February 22 (Xinhua) -- The Supreme Council of Kenya
Moslems (SUPKEM) has condemned the U.S. for its planned military
attack on Iraq and urged the world community to force Washington
to drop its invasion plans.
</P>
<P>
The Sunday Nation quoted a SUPKEM statement issued Saturday as
saying that the Arab states and most countries of the world
including three permanent members of the U.N. Security Council
were opposed to military invasion, and preferred a diplomatic
solution to the crisis.
</P>
<P>
SUPKEM urged those opposed to the military invasion to "garner
all our energies and efforts to condemn the U.S. aggression
against innocent people."
</P>
<P>
The statement noted that the seven-year blockade against Iraq
after the 1991 Gulf War had "denied the people of Iraq means to
earn their livelihood and availability of medicine for their sick
and dying".
</P>
<P>
"Currently, there is a much more serious scenario unfolding
where Britain and U.S. are beating war drums to bomb and destroy
the nation state and people of Iraq," it said.
</P>
<P>
The statement stressed that "this is under the guise of
protecting neighboring Arab states and the world community from
(possible) Iraq aggression."
</P>
<P>
"Is the U.S.A. more concerned about the security of the Arab
people than the Arabs themselves? Is the U.S.A. really upholding
the U.N. resolution?" SUPKEM questioned.
</P>
<P>
If so, it noted, "how about the Zionist state of Israel that
continues to flout 29 U.N. resolutions and persists in denying
the rights of the Palestine people?"
</P>
<P>
The council urged the world community to spare a moment to
pray for the Iraqi people and forced the U.S. government to drop
its invasion plans. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
