<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: U.S. Prepares Strike on Iraq Despite Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, February 21 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. administration
Saturday continued its preparation for possible air strikes on
Iraq despite peace efforts made by U.N. Secretary-General Kofi
Annan and demonstrations by Americans against such strikes.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. State Department advised U.S. citizens to leave Iraq
as soon as possible, accusing the Iraqi government of continuing
to "make provocative and confrontational statements indicating its
unwillingness to comply with U.N. resolutions."
</P>
<P>
In a statement, the State Department said, "all U.S. citizens
are strongly urged to avoid all travel to Iraq, and those already
in Iraq are advised to depart as soon as possible."
</P>
<P>
The administration fears that the American citizens could be
targets of terrorism because any military attack would deepen the
anti-American sentiment of the Arabs, particularly the Iraqis.
</P>
<P>
Besides the warning from the State Department, the Pentagon
also warned in a memorandum Saturday that journalists who stay in
Iraq may be at risk.
</P>
<P>
The State Department could not say how many U.S. citizens are
in Iraq, but it was reported that the number would be small as
there is no U.S. embassy in Baghdad and severe restrictions
prevented U.S. businessmen from going to Iraq.
</P>
<P>
"You should be aware that there is substantial risk involved in
sending people to Iraq during a period that could be highly
dangerous," the memorandum said.
</P>
<P>
"We will do our best to minimize civilian casualties; however,
the safety of any particular group of people, including
journalists, could be jeopardized in the event of military
action," it added.
</P>
<P>
In the White House, President Bill Clinton and his top advisors
met for about 90 minutes in the afternoon focusing on the
development in Iraq while about 3,000 anti-war demonstrators
protested outside.
</P>
<P>
Following the meeting, National Security Adviser Sandy Berger
said that U.S. military preparations are proceeding without regard
to U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan's talks with Iraqi officials
over the crisis.
</P>
<P>
White House spokesman Mike McCurry said no signs are evident
that Iraqi President Saddam Hussein wants to resolve the crisis
peacefully.
</P>
<P>
"There continue to be provocative statements issued from
Baghdad and no indication of a complete willingness to resolve
this in a peaceful fashion," he said.
</P>
<P>
As the top administration officials met, some demonstrators
gathered in a park across the street from the White House.
</P>
<P>
The protesters chanted "No more war" all the way marching about
a mile through city street before they gathered in front of the
White House with a banner holding high, which reads: "Do not bomb
Iraq."
</P>
<P>
One of the protesters said he could no longer remain silent on
the Clinton administration's marketing campaign for military
action.
</P>
<P>
"I think we have to take action if we're going to stop the
killing of a lot of innocent people," he said.
</P>
<P>
Another protester said he was "flabbergasted" that the Clinton
administration has decided to contain Iraq with bombing.
</P>
<P>
It is the first time that such a big rally took place outside
the White House. The size of Saturday's protest surprised
passers-by.
</P>
<P>
In Baghdad, Annan resumed late night talks with Iraqi Deputy
Prime Minister Tariq Aziz although the U.N. Chief said that the
mediation has been "difficult."
</P>
<P>
The official Iraqi News Agency in a brief dispatch described
the talks over the inspection of Iraqi presidential sites by U.N.
weapons experts as "difficult," but said discussions nontheless
continued.
</P>
<P>
The critical circumstances have prompted President Hussein to
chair a joint meeting of the Revolution Command Council and the
Command of Socialist Arab Baath Party earlier Saturday night to
study the Annan-Aziz talks.
</P>
<P>
Annan said he was "rather optimistic" about striking a deal
with Baghdad giving U.N. weapons inspectors' free and unrestricted
access of all suspected sites to avert a military confrontation in
the region. 
</P>
</TEXT>
