<HEADLINE> 24 Suicides Per Day in Sri Lanka </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, February 22 (Xinhua) -- Nearly 8,900 Sri Lankans
committed suicides in 1997, or more than 24 suicides per day, The
Island newspaper reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted Lakshmi Ratnayake, head of a local
organization, as saying that the latest statistics put the death
toll of suicides at 8,900 in 1997, which constituted one of the
highest rates in the world.
</P>
<P>
Ratnayake said suicide was mainly a rural phenomenon in Sri
Lanka as the highest suicide rates were reported in remote rural
areas.
</P>
<P>
The rate of suicide death was higher among males than females
and the highest age groups were the 20-30 group and the over-60
group.
</P>
<P>
Inability to cope with feelings was blamed to be the main
reason for people to take their lives. "The main reasons behind
suicides were mental depression, inability to cope with feelings
and drug and alcohol abuses," Ratnayake said. Her organization is
devoted to lending emotional support to those lonely and depressed
people.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, other experts here say poverty is another major
reason for people to commit suicide.
</P>
<P>
The government has announced to restrict access to pesticides
and other poisons last December in an effort to curb suicide
attempts of the local people. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
