<HEADLINE> France, Germany Want Earlier Admission of Poland to NATO, EU </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WARSAW, February 21 (Xinhua) -- French President Jacques Chirac
and German Federal Chancellor Helmut Kohl said Saturday that
France and Germany are willing to see an earlier admission of
Poland to the North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO) and the
European Union (EU).
</P>
<P>
Chirac and Kohl made the remarks after holding talks with
Polish President Aleksander Kwasniewski in the Polish city of
Poznan.
</P>
<P>
France and Germany will also help Poland achieve the goal, they
noted at a post-summit joint press conference.
</P>
<P>
Last July at NATO's special summit in Madrid, Hungary, Poland
and the Czech Republic were invited to enter NATO in the first
batch. They will be accepted as new members by 1999.
</P>
<P>
Kohl said that the German parliament will adopt in March or
April a draft proposal on absorbing Poland into NATO. Chirac said
the French parliament will pass the same proposal this summer.
</P>
<P>
Kohl said that his country will help Poland transform its
agriculture, heavy and military industries in its effort to join
the EU.
</P>
<P>
All the three top leaders agreed to strengthen cooperation
among the three countries in the field of culture, besides
politics and economy.
</P>
<P>
Kwasniewski proposed establishing a European University in
Poland to enhance cultural exchanges among the young generation of
Europeans.
</P>
<P>
Responding to questions about the Iraq crisis, all the three
leaders wished U.N. Secretary General Kofi Annan's mission to
Baghdad a success.
</P>
<P>
On the forthcoming French-German-Russian summit, Chirac and
Kohl agreed to brief Kwasniewski of the results of the summit.
</P>
<P>
Chirac noted that it is imperative to keep dialogues with
Russia for maintaining security in Europe.
</P>
<P>
France, Germany and Poland began to hold the three-nation
annual meetings of foreign ministers in 1991 and the regular
meetings of defense ministers in 1994. This is the first time for
the three countries to hold a summit. 
</P>
</TEXT>
