<HEADLINE> Security Beefed up in 183 Constituencies in India </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, February 22 (Xinhua) -- Security has been beefed up
in all the 183 Parliamentary constituencies as the second phase of
general elections to the 12th Lower House of Parliament began in
nine States and Union Territory of Pondicherry off the coast of
Bay Bengal on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Armed with shoot-at-sight orders, about 5,000 men drawn from
the police and paramilitary forces will be on hand to try and
ensure a "free and fair" poll in Sambhal constituency in Uttar
Pradesh. The situation has turned more tense following the
political development of government change in the State Saturday
evening with fears of large-scale violence and rigging being
fueled by statements issued by leaders of various parties.
</P>
<P>
In view of the impending developments, the police have taken
measures to prevent trouble. Apart from 1,000 men of the local
police, reinforced by 800 from nearby areas, there would be 10
companies of paramilitary forces. Besides, 100 women constables
will be deployed in the constituency, which is regarded as the
hyper-sensitive constituency in Uttar Pradesh.
</P>
<P>
The Election Commission has directed the Bihar State, where the
specter of violence looms large over the 21 Parliamentary
constituencies where the second phase of general elections is
being held Sunday, to tighten its belt and ensure that the
paramilitary forces are compulsorily deployed effectively.
</P>
<P>
According to Home Secretary R. K. Singh, the government was
keeping a strict watch on sensitive constituencies where it
apprehended violent incidents.
</P>
<P>
In the first phase of general elections held on February 16,
massive rigging and killing were reported in States of Bihar,
Uttar Pradesh, Tamil Nadu, Andhra Pradesh and other places of the
country. Over 60 people were killed and more than one hundred were
injured in various violent incidents in the elections in 222
constituencies. The Election Commission has thus forced to
announce repolling in the country time and again.
</P>
<P>
"More blasts in Coimbatore, curfew in Ajmer, home guards
looting the armory, there is little doubt that the atmosphere has
suddenly become far more tense and worrisome in the last few
days," the Hindustan Times said in its editorial on February 19.
</P>
</TEXT>
