<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka Economists Warn Against Devaluation of </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, February 22 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lanka should not panic and
devalue its currency, the Rupee, as a reaction to the current
Southeast Asian currency crisis, economists here said.
</P>
<P>
The National Chamber of Commerce of Sri Lanka said in a news
release, which was made available Sunday, that economists,
bankers, fund managers and foreign exchange dealers of the country
gathered recently to discuss possible impacts of the crisis on Sri
Lanka's economy.
</P>
<P>
It said the participants have reached a consensus that the
country should not devalue its currency.
</P>
<P>
A devaluation of the Rupee may yield short-term benefits to
exporters who are facing stiff competition from Southeast Asian
countries which have drastically devaluated their currencies.
However, in the long run, the impact is detrimental, they
cautioned.
</P>
<P>
Devaluation of the Rupee as a remedy will cause bad side
effects: rising inflation, swelling interest rates and a resultant
upward wage push, which will nullify the advantage gained by the
devaluation, an economist warned.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, those participated in the discussion identified the
areas most affected by the currency turmoil as natural rubber and
rubber products, coconut products, garments and ceramic ware.
</P>
<P>
Local businessmen have already begun to import cheaper tires
and other rubber products, they said.
</P>
<P>
They concluded that the crisis will slow down foreign
investment flow into Sri Lanka and propel the withdrawal of
foreign investments already made in the country.
</P>
<P>
Sri Lanka's exports will also lose competitiveness, especially
those dependent on local materials.
</P>
<P>
The economists pointed out that the way out is not devaluation
of currency but improvement of productivity and local savings.
Currently, the national savings in Sri Lanka is about 15 percent,
according to the bankers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980222.0158 </DOCNO>
