<HEADLINE> Used Cars From 56 Closed Firms Go Under Hammer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, February 22 (Xinhua) -- Over 20,000 bargain-hunters
flocked to three auction houses Saturday to bid for 535 cars, the
first batch of some 7,000 vehicles repossessed from the 56 closed
financial firms, the Nation newspaper reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
These vehicles were put up for sale by the financial
restructuring authority (FRA) which is responsible for the
liquidation of the failed financial firms.
</P>
<P>
FRA officials were satisfied with Saturday's auction as the
average bidding turned out to be about 10 percent above the FRA's
benchmark prices.
</P>
<P>
They expected to receive some 150 million baht (3.4 million
U.S. dollars) from the first auction, the newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
However, some people, who planned to bid for a car but returned
empty-handed, said that the prices were not as low as they had
expected.
</P>
<P>
Many people criticized the bidding arrangements as overcrowded
and chaotic. Some complained that they were not given detailed
information about the vehicles and were not allowed to drive to
test the engine.
</P>
<P>
Saturday's auction is the prelude of a series of FRA-arranged
open auctions of non-core assets, including vehicles, art crafts
and other company properties.
</P>
<P>
Sales of core assets, held through auctions to qualified
bidders, are expected to start in April and run through to the end
of the year.
</P>
<P>
The book value of the assets of the 56 firms is 866 billion
baht (19.7 billion dollars), but they will be auctioned at
discounts ranging from 30 to 60 percent, the FRA said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
