<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sino-Russian Border Trade Bucks Trend </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 22 (Xinhua) -- Although general trade between
China and Russia dipped last year, border trade between the
neighbouring giants hit new heights, according to Business Weekly
of China Daily today.
</P>
<P>
Chinese customs statistics indicate that bilateral trade in
1997 stood at 6.12 billion US dollars, down 10.5 percent from 1996.
</P>
<P>
However, border trade conducted by business people in
Mudanjiang, Heilongjiang Province, soared. According to customs
statistics, the region's border trade last year was worth 710
million US dollars, jumping 52.6 percent from 1996. the figure was
35 percent higher than in 1993, the former record year.
</P>
<P>
In Suifenhe, the border trade hub of the region, goods worth
540 million US dollars changed hands, 52 percent up from 1996.
</P>
<P>
Although the national figure for Sino-Russian border trade is
not yet available, experts believe border trade is experiencing
its second boom after overheating in the 1991-93 period.
</P>
<P>
And, the quality of this boom is better than last time. Experts
said that most of the border trade last year was done by several
large firms. The structure of the trade was also more rational.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
