<HEADLINE> Chemical Sector to Boost Exports </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 22 (Xinhua) -- Pressure from the woes of
Southeast Asia and the demands of industrial restructuring is
building on China's chemical industry, which is seeking a way out
by exploring overseas markets.
</P>
<P>
Developing nations in Africa, Eastern Europe and the
Commonwealth of Independent States will become the priorities in
market expansion, reported today's China Daily quoting Gu Xiulian,
minister of chemical industry.
</P>
<P>
She also encouraged domestic chemical companies to accelerate
investment in Southeast Asia, which is experiencing unprecedented
currency depreciation.
</P>
<P>
The minister urged chemical enterprises to establish production
bases for exports and sales in other nations.
</P>
<P>
"The financial turmoil in Southeast Asia will inevitably affect
out exports in 1998, therefore we must spare no efforts to bring
down costs, improve quality and increase productivity," she said.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry of Chemical Industry (MCI) has set the target of
this year's exports at 16 billion US dollars, up one billion US
dollars from 1997.
</P>
<P>
The major chemical items for export include dyestuff,
pesticides, tyres, rubber shoes, soda ash and caustic soda.
</P>
<P>
Gu predicted growth of 8 percent for the chemical sector this
year. 
</P>
