<HEADLINE> China to Launch Ten More Satellites </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 22 (Xinhua) -- China is set to launch ten
more satellites before the end of the century, according to Xu
Fuxiang, director of the Chinese Academy of Space
Technology (CAST).
</P>
<P>
These satellites will include the Sino-Brazilian Earth
Resources Satellite, and a series of other satellites designed for
earth observations, navigation and global positioning,
and scientific experimentation, according to Xu.
</P>
<P>
Xu said the Earth Resources Satellite, or ZY-1, and a smaller
satellite will be launched within this year. In addition, an
advanced earth observation satellite and various smaller
satellites are scheduled for launch during 1999.
</P>
<P>
China has launched 40 satellites designed by CAST over the past
30 years, including telecommunications and broadcast,
meteorological and scientific experimentation satellites.
</P>
<P>
The Dongfanghong-4 (DFH-4), a high capacity telecommunications
satellite, is currently in the development stage, according to
Xu. 
</P>
</TEXT>
