<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Holdups to Teamsters in Brazilian Roads Up in 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
RIO DE JANEIRO, Februray 21 (Xinhua) -- Holdups to teamsters in
the Brazilian highways caused last year economic losses for more
than 118 million dollars, sector sources said on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Data provided by the Sao Paulo Syndicate of Cargo
Transportation Companies of Sao Paulo and Regions (SETCESP) showed
that 1,069 cargo trucks were held up in all the country, a figure
that represents a 16.06 percent increase over the number
registered in 1996.
</P>
<P>
According to the sources, the products most frequently stolen
were textiles and apparel, and foodstuffs. The country registered
in 1997 168 robberies of textile and apparel products, 15 percent
of the thefts of cargo on the roads. The theft of foodstuffs was
second with 128 cases of theft, 11.98 percent of the total.
</P>
<P>
SETCESP informed that the Brazilian state of Sao Paulo
registered last year 439 cases of robbery of cargoes, meaning
41.07 percent of the total number of stick-ups.
</P>
<P>
On the other hand, the Brazilian Association of the Frigorifics
Industry (ABIF), said that 64 of its trucks were held up in the
city of Sao Paulo in the last days of this month, causing a loss
of almost 10 million dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
