<HEADLINE> Anti-War Protest Held in Front of White House </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, February 21 (Xinhua) -- About 3,000 people Saturday
mounted a protest against a possible U.S. air strike on Iraq in
front of the White House.
</P>
<P>
They chanted "No more war" all the way to the front gate of the
White House through city street, holding high a banner which reads
"Do not bomb Iraq."
</P>
<P>
U.S. President Bill Clinton was at the time holding a meeting
with his foreign policy team on how to proceed with military
preparations during U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan's talks with
Iraqi officials on possible ways to defuse the current crisis over
weapons inspections in Iraq.
</P>
<P>
It was the first time that an anti-war protest has been taken
to the White House.
</P>
<P>
Last week, Secretary of State Madeleine Albright, Defense
Secretary William Cohen and U.N. Ambassador Bill Richardson were
greeted with anti-war protests at Ohio State University when they
tried to spell out the reason for a military action against Iraq.
</P>
<P>
A protester said he could no longer remain silent on the
Clinton administration's marketing campaign for military action.
</P>
<P>
"I think we have to take action if we're going to stop the
killing of a lot of innocent people," he said.
</P>
<P>
Another protester said he was "flabbergasted" that the Clinton
administration has decided to contain Iraq with bombing.
</P>
<P>
The size of Saturday's protest surprised passers-by.
</P>
<P>
"It's more than I expected," a man said. "I guess I didn't
realize how strongly people felt about it." 
</P>
</TEXT>
