<HEADLINE> Panamanian Banana Workers' Strike Causes Big Losses </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PANAMA CITY, February 21 (Xinhua) -- The strike of more than
4,000 banana workers of Panama's Chiriqui Land Company, now on its
third day, has already caused big losses while some 28,000 heads
of banana per day cannot be processed in time.
</P>
<P>
Experts in banana business estimated a loss of 1.3 million
U.S. dollars a week if the stoppage, which started Thursday,
continued.
</P>
<P>
The strike was triggered by the paralyzing of a dock along the
Pacific coast two months ago.
</P>
<P>
A drop in banana demand along the eastern coast of the United
States prompted Chiriqui to stop using Port Armuelles. Instead,
the company decided to ship the fruit from other ports along the
Atlantic coast.
</P>
<P>
The decision left 270 employees idle at Port Armuelles, and the
striking workers wanted the company to address the needs of the
idle employees. 
</P>
</TEXT>
