<HEADLINE> Highlights of Major Beijing-based Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 22 (Xinhua) -- Highlights of today's major
Beijing-based Newspapers:
</P>
<P>
"People's Daily"
</P>
<P>
-- Northeast China's Liaoning Province and Hebei and Shanxi
provinces in north China have mobilized massive workforce
to build a batch of anti-drought facilities, to ensure the coming
spring ploughing to go smoothly.
</P>
<P>
-- Front-paged are two pieces of photograph which describe many
visitors paying respects to the outstanding late Chinese Premier
Zhou Enlai before a relics and photo exhibition in Beijing, on the
occasion of the upcoming centenary of the birth of Zhou.
</P>
<P>
A total of 120 artistic works from Huaiyin City in east China's
Jiangsu Province, Zhou's hometown, were also exhibited here.
</P>
<P>
Nanjing, capital of Jiangsu, opened a Zhou Enlai Library
yesterday at Meiyuan Xincun, headquarters of the Chinese Communist
Party delegation headed by the late Premier during the early stage
of the War of Liberation (1945-1949).
</P>
<P>
"Xinhua Daily Telegraph"
</P>
<P>
-- Chongqing, one of the six old industrial bases in China,
vows to provide job opportunities for 100,000 laid-off people in
1998.
</P>
<P>
The southwestern municipality had 200,000 jobless people at the
end of 1997, one of the cities with largest amount of such people.
</P>
<P>
-- The earthquake-hit Zhangjiakou area in north China's Hebei
Province has, so far, received more than 70 million yuan of
donations for disaster relief efforts from both home and abroad.
</P>
<P>
-- Over the past decade, south China's Guangdong Province has
invested 29.2 billion yuan to build water control and hydropower
projects.
</P>
<P>
"China Daily"
</P>
<P>
-- China's international contractors will step up efforts to
tap the market potential of Africa and Latin America, according to
an official of the Ministry of Foreign Trade and Economic
Cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Chinese contractors signed new contracts worth 1.73 billion US
dollars in Africa last year, up 14.9 percent from 1996 and
accounting for 15.3 percent of all new contracts signed last year.
</P>
<P>
-- The severe financial crisis that has rocked the countries of
East and Southeast Asia has cast a shadow on China's external
economic cooperation, 70 percent of which takes place in the
region in the form of engineering contracts and labor services.
</P>
