<HEADLINE> Italians Protest Against Possible U.S. Strike on Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, February 21 (Xinhua) -- Italians held demonstrations
Saturday, protesting at the United States' threat of use of force
against Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Police said that the number of demonstrators in Rome and Milan
had reached 2,000 and 5,000 respectively, joined by leaders of
Reconstructed Communism and the Green Party.
</P>
<P>
They marched through streets, carrying placards, some of which
read "No Bombs on Children" and "U.S. Soldiers are Slaughterers"
while others voiced support for the Iraqi people.
</P>
<P>
Similar demonstrations were held in the cities of Florence,
Genoa, Assisi and Ancona.
</P>
<P>
As part of the ruling Alliance of the Central and Left,
Reconstructed Communism and the Green Party were strongly opposed
to U.S. troops using Italian bases to launch attacks on Iraq.
</P>
<P>
If the government allows U.S. troops to use the military bases
in Italy, they will withdraw from the government, they warned.
</P>
</TEXT>
