<HEADLINE> Italy Optimistic Over Annan's Iraq Mission </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, February 21 (Xinhua) -- United Nations Secretary General
Kofi Annan told Italian Prime Minister Romano Prodi over phone
Saturday afternoon that he was rather optimistic after the first
round of talks with Iraqi Deputy Prime Minister Tareq Aziz.
</P>
<P>
Annan arrived in Baghdad, Iraq, Friday in an effort to seek a
diplomatic solution to the crisis of weapons inspections in Iraq.
</P>
<P>
His visit there was widely regarded as the last-ditch mission
to avoid a possible U.S. military strike against Iraq.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. chief has completed two rounds of plenary talks with
Iraqi officials and planned to meet Iraqi President Saddam Hussein
on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Annan told Prodi that he gave a minute explanation of the
United Nations stand over the crisis.
</P>
<P>
Prodi said Italy fully supports the U.N. diplomatic efforts and
stressed dialogue should continue.
</P>
<P>
Also on Saturday, Italian Foreign Minister Lamberto Dini said
he was optimistic that a diplomatic solution to the Iraq crisis
was possible.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with the daily newspaper La Repubblica, Dini
said, "I have full confidence. I'm convinced that diplomatic
negotiations can take all the time necessary." 
</P>
</TEXT>
