<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hi-tech Industries Boom in Shanghai </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, February 22 (Xinhua) -- Shanghai, an economic
powerhouse in east China, witnessed a rapid growth in its high
technology industries last year.
</P>
<P>
Official figures showed that the municipality's hi-tech output
reached 54 billion yuan in 1997, contributing to more than 15
percent of its total industrial output.
</P>
<P>
Information, bio-medicines and new materials industries made up
the bulk of Shanghai's total hi-tech output, with their earnings
rising over 30 percent to 52 billion yuan last year.
</P>
<P>
The information industry led the way with output value worth 28
billion yuan, among which 18 billion yuan came from the
communications industry.
</P>
<P>
In 1997, production of eight kinds of new bio-medicines were
approved while 45 projects passed clinical research trials in
Shanghai.
</P>
<P>
The local government also worked out a plan to speed up
construction of 90 projects in the new materials industry.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai has vowed to become one of the most important global
economic centres early next century. In such an effort, banking
and hi-tech industries have been given priority for development.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980222.0204 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Romania, Moldova to Strengthen Economic Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAREST, February 21 (Xinhua) -- Visiting Moldovan President
Peter Luchinsky and Romanian President Emil Constantinescu agreed
Saturday to strengthen bilateral cooperation, especially in the
economic field.
</P>
<P>
Luchinsky, who was on a one-day working visit to Romania, and
Constantinescu held in-depth talks in the Romanian city of Galati
on how to enhance bilateral economic cooperation, particularly on
the establishment of free economic zones.
</P>
<P>
Under a plan for promoting economic cooperation among Romania,
Moldova and Ukraine, three free economic zones would be set up in
the Lasi-Ungheni region of Romania, the Reni region of Ukraine and
the Galati-Giurgiulesti region across Romania and Moldova.
</P>
<P>
During the talks, the two presidents also exchanged views on
the opening of branches of Romanian commercial banks and
cooperative banks in Moldova, the establishment of furniture joint
ventures, the export of Moldovan-made medicines to Romania, and
the promotion of cooperation in energy.
</P>
<P>
On the battle against the escalating organized crime, the two
presidents shared the view that the cooperation between the two
countries' customs officers and border guards should be
strengthened. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
